AU  - Sarah C. Caso
TI  - The Reproductive Health of Osmia lignaria and Osmia cornifrons (Hymenoptera: Megachilidae) along an Urban Gradient
PY  - 2024
PB  - University of California, Berkeley
UR  - https://www.ocf.berkeley.edu/~pkmendez/envsci/projects/2024final/CasoS_2024.pdf
U1  - CasoS_2024-page1.pdf
AB  - As urban development increases, there is a need to understand how land development and population growth impacts local wildlife. In particular, pollinators such as bees. Urbanization has been shown to harm bee populations, while urban environments have also been found to serve as an oasis for bees. In this study, I examined how the reproductive health of two species of Mason bees, Osmia sp., in Sacramento and Davis, CA are affected by urbanization. Two different species were studied: O. lignaria and O. cornifrons. To answer this question, I studied these bees in five different localizations: highly urbanized big city, urbanized big city, urbanized small city, suburbs of a small city, and agricultural areas. Trap nests with brood cells were placed this gradient in Yolo County, California. Nests with the newly produced brood cells were collected from the nests several weeks later to determine their reproductive health and reproductive success; that is, the size of nests, number of broods produced per nest, the mass of the broods, the sex ratio of the broods, and the ratio of healthy broods produced to total eggs laid. I conclude that urban landscapes can serve as beneficial environments for Mason bees. The size of nests, number of broods, and sex ratio was not significantly impacted by urbanization, but urbanized small city sites produced larger bees and had higher reproductive success rates, indicating that urban environments produce healthier offspring. The results of this study have implications for the conservation of solitary, cavity-nesting bees in urban environments.
