TI  - Identifying Contributors to Green Gentrification: A Comparative Study of Atlanta and San Francisco
PY  - 2024
PB  - University of California, Berkeley
UR  - https://www.ocf.berkeley.edu/~pkmendez/envsci/projects/2024final/KalawM_2024.pdf
U1  - KalawM_2024-page1.pdf
AB  - Urban green space (UGS) developments, though beneficial for environmental and public health, are often sited in areas that can have the unintended consequence of increasing housing costs in areas surrounding the green spaces. This could lead to gentrification and displacement of existing residents, which paradoxically would harm the nearby low-income and BIPOC neighborhoods that UGS are meant to benefit. Existing research on green gentrification (GG) are mostly case studies that point to site-specific factors of gentrification, making it difficult to broadly approach UGS planning with a common set of anti-gentrification factors. Thus, this study aims to use calculations of change and geographically weighted regression in ArcGIS to identify a common feature of green space that most strongly explains gentrification occurring across two cities which have experienced varying levels of GG. I found that the number of green spaces in a census tract was the most consistent, but not the strongest explanatory factor for green gentrification occurring across both cities, while proximity to UGS was indicative of GG occurring in San Francisco, but not Atlanta. These results are consistent with Atlanta being a “leading” GG city and suggest that other factors or combinations of factors, such as uses or maintenance of green spaces, should also be considered in UGS planning to avoid gentrification and displacement of low-income and BIPOC residents.
