TI  - How Modeling Can Be Used to Predict the Effects of Climate Change on Philippine Coral Reef Ecosystems
PY  - 2024
PB  - University of California, Berkeley
UR  - https://www.ocf.berkeley.edu/~pkmendez/envsci/projects/2024final/MabasaN_2024.pdf
U1  - MabasaN_2024-page1.pdf
AB  - Climate change will amplify the effects of ocean acidification and coral bleaching, the two main threats to the health of coral reef ecosystems. However, it is uncertain as to what extent climate change will harm coral reef ecosystems within the next decade. Modeling studies have been conducted to understand the future possibilities to predict the effects of climate change on coral reef ecosystems and evaluate the outcome. Here I conduct a literature review on predictive studies that could be used to examine the effects of climate change on coral reef ecosystems in the Philippines. These studies show that while predictive modeling has been used to guide climate policies, they are ultimately limited by the inability to account for factors external to each model. These studies work for specific trends, such as observing the increase in species biomass in a given study area but are ultimately unable to realistically reflect the future on a larger scale due to the unpredictable nature of climate change and its effects.
