AB  - The Fukushima Daiichi nuclear disaster of March 2011 precipitated a multifaceted challenge in managing the resulting contaminated water at the Fukushima Daiichi Nuclear Power Plant. Accumulation of contaminated water from cooling processes and groundwater seepage has necessitated urgent action to address limited storage capacity. One proposed solution is the ocean discharge of treated wastewater, which has sparked debates and raised concerns among stakeholders. This paper provides an overview of the Fukushima Daiichi disaster, examines the rationale behind the ocean discharge proposal, and assesses its potential benefits and drawbacks. Drawing on stakeholder perspectives, including those of the Japanese government, local residents, and the international community, the paper explores the complexities of decision-making in managing nuclear wastewater. It highlights the importance of balancing environmental, health, and economic considerations and emphasizes the need for continued dialogue, transparency, and collaboration in navigating this complex issue. By synthesizing available evidence and research findings, this paper contributes to a nuanced understanding of the environmental and societal implications of nuclear waste water release in Japan, emphasizing the importance of informed decision-making and effective risk communication in nuclear waste management.
