AB  - Urban expansion has increased the prevalence of single-family residences with gardens that provide various ecosystem services to both humans and the environment. However, to optimize the benefits of these gardens, residents must consider both the design choices and subsequent benefits. I surveyed 308 residents in Berkeley, California, to determine how residential gardens can be designed to provide the most welfare for homeowners and their communities. I analyzed three pathways: (1) What are the motivations and outcomes for residents who have adopted low-input or native landscape design practices? (2) What aspects of a garden are associated with greater benefit (overall satisfaction or improvements in stress relief) for the resident? (3) How can we qualitatively understand residents' relationships with and aspirations for their gardens? Sixty percent of respondents who had replaced at least some plants in their garden with native or drought resistant varieties did so in order to reduce water use. However, fewer than half of this group reported an actual reduction in water consumption, representing a disconnect between the perceived and actual benefits of implementing a native or low-input design strategy. When examining the relationships between garden characteristics and indicators of benefit, I found that the time each respondent spent in their garden each week positively impacted reported stress relief. Moreover, individuals who are most satisfied with their garden most often expressed a desire to be more involved, suggesting that taking the time to establish a relationship with one's garden is the most effective way to derive benefit from it.
