TY  - THES
AU  - Thảo Nguyên (Sarah) Bùi
TI  - Co-Benefits of Bridges Construction in the Mekong Delta
PY  - 2021
PB  - University of California, Berkeley
UR  - https://www.ocf.berkeley.edu/~pkmendez/envsci/projects/2021final/BuiS_2021.pdf
U1  - BuiS_2021-page1.pdf
AB  - This study analyzes the impact of bridge construction on air pollution in the Mekong Delta. This region relies on ferry systems to cross dense river networks. Millions of dollars have been invested in the region to build roads and bridges, replacing the existing ferry systems. As transportation is the biggest source of air pollution in the region and traffic volume is increasing yearly, the effect of these bridges on air pollution is unknown. Using remote sensing satellite-based data, OMI for NO₂ and MODIS for Aerosol, and econometrics models, the operation of the bridges estimates a decrease in NO₂ by 7.269 × 10¹³ molecules/cm³, controlling for nearby powerplants, temperature, humidity, El Niño, and monthly fluctuations. Wider bridge width and larger bridge area estimates greater decrease in NO₂ by 0.460 × 10¹³ molecules/cm³ and 0.0002 × 10¹³ molecules/cm³ with an additional meter of bridge width and meter squared of bridge area respectively. In contrast, there is little to no change in particulate matter. This effect is a result of the closure of ferry services, as ferries used bunker fuels, which emit more nitrogen oxides than gasolines of road vehicles. However, the replacement of ferries with bridges is not sustainable, as many discontinued ferry services are returning back to accommodate short distance commuting needs and rising traffic congestion at newly built bridges.
KW  - air pollution
KW  - nitrogen dioxide
KW  - aerosol
KW  - remote sensing
KW  - transportation investment
