TY  - THES
AU  - Jasmine Y. Casey
TI  - An Approach to Land-Use Suitability Analysis in the Sacramento-San Joaquin Delta Based on Flooding Hazard
PY  - 2021
PB  - University of California, Berkeley
UR  - https://www.ocf.berkeley.edu/~pkmendez/envsci/projects/2021final/CaseyJ_2021.pdf
U1  - CaseyJ_2021-page1.pdf
AB  - As we begin to experience the impacts of climate change, we must alter our land use to fit the new
climatic realities, including increasing risk of flood. The Sacramento-San Joaquin Delta is an area
of specific interest and concern, due to its important role in terms of human, environmental, and
agricultural land use. With increased demands on the Delta from development and urbanization
along with the pressures of increased flood risk, current land use in the Delta will not be sustainable
in the future. I developed maps of flood risk in 100-year storm events in various sea level rise
scenarios (SLR 0m, 0.5m, 1.0m, and 1.41m) and how it would affect land use in the Delta. I used
GIS to facilitate my analysis of current land use, future flood risk, and zoning regulations. As sea
level rise increased, the extent and depth of flooded land increased dramatically. I determined that
the majority of the Delta is zoned for agricultural use and that agricultural land will be most
affected in any given flood scenario. The urbanized areas of East Contra Costa County and
Stockton will be affected if sea level increases by 1.0 meter. Additionally, residents living the
Primary Zone of the Delta will be affected even in a 0 meter sea level rise scenario. Resident in
the Primary Zone of the Delta must be informed of flood risks and plan for the transitioning of
land use as agricultural land and residences become unsustainable and uninhabitable.
KW  - GIS
KW  - spatial analysis
KW  - zoning
KW  - environmental planning
KW  - wetlands
