TI  - The Potential Impact of Human Consumption on the Population of Asian Carp in America
PY  - 2021
PB  - University of California, Berkeley
UR  - https://www.ocf.berkeley.edu/~pkmendez/envsci/projects/2021final/Guoz_2021.pdf
U1  - Guoz_2021-page1.pdf
AB  - The freshwater ecosystem can be vulnerable to threats of species invasion. Asian Carp is one of the invasive species that occur in the contiguous United States; it is a common food in many Asian countries, but it has been causing damages to not only the native ecosystem but also aquacultural industries in the United States. The U.S. government has not yet given effective policies to solve the invasion problem of Asian Carp at present. Based on the fact of human consumption of the Carp in Asia, I researched the potential of population control of Asian carp in North America by encouraging an increase in human consumption. I surveyed Chinese students at Berkeley about their understanding of the species as well as their willingness of consuming them and their reasons. I also interviewed domestic students at Berkeley in Environmental Sciences major about their concerns about consuming the carp. The results showed that Chinese students were having fewer concerns about eating the Asian Carp based on better cognitions, but their decisions were affected by personal preferences. Domestic students were having overall limited cognition about Asian Carp; they had common concerns about food safety and ecological protection. The results provided a way to conclude possible factors that affect people’s attitudes towards eating the Asian Carp. Encouraging an increase in human consumption is a potential way to control the invasion of Asian carp.
KW  - Invasive species
KW  - Asian Carp
KW  - novel foods
