PB  - University of California, Berkeley
UR  - https://www.ocf.berkeley.edu/~pkmendez/envsci/projects/2021final/ManansalaJ_2021.pdf
U1  - ManansalaJ_2021-page1.pdf
AB  - In recent years, the Bay Area has been frequently exposed to wildfire smoke and it has been affecting the health of many individuals and communities. The aim of my research is to understand how the recent fires within the Bay Area are affecting the health of people by using air quality data. I used two air quality sensors from the Bay Area Air Quality Management District (BAAQMD) with a focus on two sites within West Oakland (West Oakland Sensor) and Eastside San Jose (Knox Avenue Sensor). Using these sensors, I aimed to answer: (a) What is the relationship between smoke levels and particulate matter 2.5 (PM2.5)? And (b) Does constant and consistent periods of ’poor’ to ’unhealthy’ air quality resulting from wildfire smoke affect the respiratory health of nearby communities and individuals? With these questions in mind, the design of this research will look into the trends to find out if wildfire smoke is affecting individuals. Using time-series analysis, I found a significantly increasing trend in PM2.5 concentrations in Knox Avenue and West Oakland sites (p-value = 3.43x10^-5 and p-value = 1.99x10^-15, respectively). The time-series trend test on the number of asthma emergency department visits failed to show any significant trends over the 2016-2018 period in Knox Avenue and West Oakland sites (p-value = 0.07 and p-value = 0.25 respectively). Overall, this study gives insight into changes in air quality and particulate matter resulting from wildfire smoke, but is inconclusive regarding the association with asthma emergency room visits. Increases in wildfire activity and worsening air quality are expected over the next few decades.
KW  - Wildfires
