UR  - https://www.ocf.berkeley.edu/~pkmendez/envsci/projects/2021final/OylerH_2021.pdf
U1  - OylerH_2021-page1.pdf
AB  - Global lockdowns resulting from the COVID-19 pandemic introduced many movement restrictions to daily life in 2020. These restrictions may have impacted the public’s ability to contribute to citizen science data collection. I investigated how the pandemic has affected citizen science by examining birdwatching observations submitted to eBird. I looked at observation counts, user recruitment, species of special concern counts, and land cover observation distribution in Alameda County from the years 2017 through 2020. Compared to previous years, 2020 showed small but not significant increases in observation count and new user recruitment with 3.7 million total observations from 1,641 total observers. Similarly, there was a small but not significant increase in observations of vulnerable species from the California Department of Fish and Wildlife’s species of special concern list with 10,515 observations, accounting for less than 1% of total observations. Observations did not shift between urban and non-urban locations with an average of 25% of observations being made in urban areas among the four years. This study demonstrates that birders in Alameda County consistently used eBird even under the movement restrictions caused by the pandemic. Citizen science data is important to conservation planning and decision-making. Understanding how the COVID-19 pandemic has affected citizen science data collection is essential to help scientists properly interpret and use this data in future studies.
KW  - eBird
