AU  - Anna C. Ramji
TI  - Finding what tries to not be found: Analyzing patterns in cryptic behavior of Octopus chierchiae in laboratory settings
PY  - 2021
PB  - University of California, Berkeley
UR  - https://www.ocf.berkeley.edu/~pkmendez/envsci/projects/2021final/RamjiA_2021.pdf
U1  - RamjiA_2021-page1.pdf
AB  - Crypsis is an essential evolutionary adaptation of octopuses which allows them to outsmart predators and prey alike, as they fight to overcome the vulnerability of their shell-less mollusc ancestry. Camouflaging is one example of cryptic behavior in which specialized skin cells are controlled in a complex neurological and physiological system to imitate pigment, light, and even texture. Several species of octopus, including Octopus chierchiae, can also bury or cover themselves in substrate and debris to evade detection and predation. Though the common octopuses’ (O. vulgaris) temporal organization of responses to predator activity has been studied, preference in modes of cryptic behavior have not previously been explored (Meisel, D. et al. 2013). This study addresses the complexity and preferences of O. chierchiae behavior on both individual and population scales in the context of controlled laboratory environments. I also explore the potential to establish a baseline of consistencies in individual behavior.
