U1  - CervantesHernandezD_2019-page1.pdf
AB  - The Sacramento-San Joaquin River Delta is among one of the most important water sources in California as it provides water for irrigation to the Central Valley and urban uses for Southern California. The Delta is a highly altered ecosystem due to the transformation of estuarine habitat such as wetlands and marshes to agricultural land. I used abiotic and biotic factors to analyze their effects on the structure of fish assemblages in the Delta. Multivariate analysis approaches such as Principal Component analysis (PCA) and Non-Metric Multidimensional scaling (NMDS) were utilized to identify the structure of fish assemblages among four habitat types and seven geographic locations in the Delta. Both PCA and NMDS plots did not show significant evidence that environmental factors within habitats and location influence the structure of native and non-native fish assemblages. Species co-occurrence analysis results identified some positive association between native and non-native species in the Delta which could provide information on the structure of fish assemblages for future studies.
