AB  - The objective of this study is to determine if there is a significant difference in primary production between varying seagrass cover densities: bare sediment, high-density of seagrass, and low-density seagrass and to quantify it. To estimate and quantify the impacts of habitat fragmentation on seagrass ecosystems in the central Red Sea, I used primary production as a proxy. Primary production was quantified by day and night in-situ incubations that recorded oxygen fluxes using a sensor to estimate GPP, R and NPP. Moreover, water samples at the start and end of each incubation were taken to record DIC fluxes, which could also be used to determine GPP, R and NPP values. The trends in the oxygen flux data and the DIC flux data were compared to each other to determine accuracy. These values were also compared to estimates made in other scientific papers to assess the accuracy of values concerning the decrease in the carbon sequestration capabilities given current rates of global seagrass depletion. I expect that primary production will decrease within seagrass meadows as they shift in density from more vegetated substrate samples to unvegetated substrate samples. This decrease in primary productivity would also be apparent in decreased levels of organic carbon being created by primary producers and hence less nutrients available for consumers in subsequent trophic levels. The findings of this study will be important for management of coastal development by demonstrating the impact of habitat fragmentation on seagrass beds in the Red Sea.
KW  - Oxygen flux
