AB  - Little is known about the patterns of fecal contamination in rural Bangladeshi households, specifically transmission pathways of pathogenic Escherichia coli. By understanding these disease transmission patterns, more effective sanitation intervention can be introduced to relieve the diarrheal disease burden of these communities. We analyzed soil (N=749), stored water (N=732), mother hand (N=734), and children hand samples (N=372) collected from approximately 720 households in the central floodplain of rural Bangladesh for the presence of five different pathogenic E. coli gene types. Pathogenic E. coli was highly prevalent in all sample types: 59% of soil samples, 32% of children hands, 21% of mother hands, and 37% of stored water samples tested positive for at least one gene type of pathogenic E. coli. There were statistically significant associations between all combinations of sample types for differing pathogenic E. coli gene types, the strongest being between mother hands and children hands (X^2 = 11.5; p < 0.001). Pathogenic E. coli of animal origin were present in every statistically significant pathway except mother hands and stored water, suggesting domestic animal presence plays a large role in disease transmission in rural Bangladesh. There were no strong similarities in trends between temperature and precipitation and the presence of pathogenic E. coli, and soil moisture content was only weakly informative. Soil, animal presence, and child behavior are key in understanding the patterns of pathogenic E. coli transmission within households of rural Bangladesh. Future modeling these transmission pathways will allow us to better understand the directionality of these findings.
