AB  - Community solar is the latest solar energy deployment business model that is gaining popularity across California. Even though there are significant economic and environmental benefits of pursuing this untapped market, identifying possible community solar locations and customers is complicated and costly. The objective of this research is to run an economic analysis to see if the net percent savings of opting into a community solar program is greater than the net percent savings of owning residential solar based on geographical location and consumer energy consumption behavior. This research is a parametric study containing 50 cities in California and eight different California load profiles. I ran these parameters on the optimization program DER-CAM to find cost savings of different scenarios and examined if consumers are better off with purchasing residential solar panels or joining a community solar program.
