PB  - University of California, Berkeley
UR  - https://www.ocf.berkeley.edu/~pkmendez/envsci/projects/2018final/MannanS_2018.pdf
U1  - MannanS_2018-page1.pdf
AB  - Microgrids are a standalone power generation solution to the problem of remote, unelectrified communities. However, financing microgrids remains challenging due to various risks. This includes microgrid versus-national grid conflicts, which occur when unanticipated national grid extension overtakes established microgrids. Current predictions for national grid extension use static forecasts based on current conditions and do not account for dynamism inherent in national grid extension, which can lead to incorrect extension forecasts. To reduce microgrid-national grid conflicts and better predict grid extension, I developed a dynamic model to predict national grid extension to a higher degree of accuracy than static forecasting using an iterative Monte Carlo Simulation over a series of time steps in three townships Saw, Kanpetlet and Mindat in Myanmar. I used breakeven distance, the point where both national grid extension and a microgrid cost the same to build at that location, to determine grid extension probability each year. I then determined if the grid would extend to each township each year. I found that electrification of one township led to increased probability of grid extension to the two surrounding townships. Mindat (township three), which had a 0% chance of extension when looked at from a static viewpoint, had a 100% chance of extension in year three of the dynamic model. Breakeven distances increased over time and all townships were electrified by year four. Dynamic modelling provides a more accurate forecast of grid extension probability over time than static forecasting. This can improve microgrid siting and rural community electrification rates.
KW  - Monte Carlo Simulation
