U1  - RomeroR_2018-page1.pdf
AB  - Climate education’s short and long-term influence on students is not well documented, and the effectiveness of current climate education is not fully understood. I conducted research with 11 middle school students at an after school program in Berkeley, California. I created an educational intervention that comprised an academic video about climate science that I accessed from YouTube, and a follow-up group discussion. I used pre-surveys, post-surveys, and interviews to gauge any change in students’ reported knowledge, concern, or actions regarding climate change. My findings were similar to those of other similar studies but also provided new insight into the effectiveness of current education in shaping students’ engagement with climate change. Like most adolescents elsewhere, the respondents understood the existence and the anthropogenic nature of climate change. Generally, the students understood consequences of climate change, but were less certain about causes and potential mitigating actions. Also, there was a clear difference between which causes, consequences, and actions were universally understood, and which were most confusing for the students. However, by improving their knowledge in all three areas, they demonstrated the capacity to learn from both the video and the discussion. Overall, they had concern and demonstrated eagerness to discuss the topic, but this did not translate to changing their behaviors outside of the classroom. Future research needs to address why students do not do more to help mitigate climate change despite their awareness and concern, and how we can best increase long-term motivation to engage in pro-environmental behaviors and lifestyles.
KW  - climate science
