AB  - Global climate change results in increasing chances of extreme weathers; drought is one of the negative ecological consequences. The recent California drought resulted in a decreased amount of precipitation, snowpack, groundwater, etc. These drought conditions resulted in tree death. A study from Stanford University presented that drought triggered tree mortality (Breshears, et, al, 2005). As victims in the drought period, trees suffer damage because of the lack of water causes damages on plants xylem. When xylem suffers too much damage, it loses the ability to recover, and it loses its function to transport sap (Skelton, et, al, 2017). As a result, it reduces both respiration and photosynthesis activities in this induvial. On a bigger scale, when many of the trees are damaged, the productivity of that area decreases. It directly affects the Carbon Dioxide concentration in that area. Because the plants lose some of their function, their ability to soak up Carbon Dioxide weakens. When Carbon Dioxide concentration keeps rising, it may amplify on globe warming (Dai, A. 2010), which comes back to increase the chance of having an extreme drought, and more trees are damaged in the drought (Brodribb et al, 2016). The acknowledgment of unrecoverable damage point on trees is a valuable information for forest reservation and water management. Our ability to predict tree dieback is lacking, and my study is an investigation that tries to answer this unknown.
KW  - embolism
