AB  - Concrete is one of the most widely consumed materials on Earth. Portland cement production accounts for 74% of carbon dioxide emissions associated with concrete and 5% of total anthropogenic emissions. Void formers have been traditionally used as a method to reduce the self-weight of concrete slabs while maintaining structural integrity, but have also recently been promoted as an effective means to reduce concrete and cement consumption. BubbleDeck was invented in 1995 and has been shown to reduce the self-weight of concrete slabs and reduce material consumption. However, the comprehensive environmental impact of BubbleDeck voided slabs, specifically in the North American context, has been minimally addressed. Life-cycle assessment is method by which the total environmental impact of a product over its life stages is measured from production through end-of-life use. Using previously determined global warming potential values of concrete, steel reinforcement bar (i.e. rebar), and high-density polyethylene, a comparative life-cycle assessment of three sizes of structurally comparable solid and voided slabs was conducted. The assessment suggests that incorporating BubbleDeck void formers can significantly reduce the global warming potential of otherwise solid slabs by up to 74%, and may be an effective method of reducing carbon emissions associated with concrete production.
KW  - global warming potential (GWP)
