U1  - CenS_2017-page1.pdf
AB  - Machine Learning is rarely used to estimate country-level Biocapacity based on Bio-Physical data (BP) and Socio-Economic data(SE). In this study, I proposed and tested the assumption that a non-linear model has better prediction ability than a linear model in country-level cropland Biocapacity prediction. I selected and tested Artificial Neural Network(ANN) and Multivariate Linear Regression(MLR)for two models on three scenarios. The dataset is separated into three models to describe three scenarios of predictor data: Bio-Physical, Socio-Economic(SE) and BP-SE-Combined. Both ANN and MLR were used to train on these three scenarios independently. The best prediction result is the BP-SE-Combined Scenario, of which the test set regression resulted in ANN having the lowest RMSE value of 0.03603 and a highest R² value of 0.97495 among all three scenarios, which indicates that ANN has the potential of building better model fit in country-level Biocapacity prediction. However, as a result of the scarcity of datapoint, data dropping problem during data pre-processing procedure and data downscaling during pre-training process, RMSE of ANN is still high when scaling the prediction back to original value. For ANN, RMSE increased to 3.9 × 10⁵ after scaling. Currently, without more complete and aggregated source data for BP data such as water usage, country-level averaged precipitation or SE data such as financial support flow to Agriculture, ANN should not be applied directly for country level cropland Biocapacity prediction.
