PB  - University of California, Berkeley
UR  - https://www.ocf.berkeley.edu/~pkmendez/envsci/projects/2017final/HungK_2017.pdf
U1  - HungK_2017-page1.pdf
AB  - As warming trends in California are expected to rise by the end of the century, there are rising concerns that elevated temperatures and high temperature extreme could directly increase individuals’ heat-related health risks including heat stroke, heat exhaustion, cardiovascular and respiratory problems. Many studies in other highly populated urban areas have found that increase in temperature leads to an increase in cardiovascular mortality rate. High proportion of populations in California lack the ability to cope with changing conditions; hence, they might face the same consequences if local institutions are not informed about heat adaptive or mitigation strategies. After conducting a multivariable regression analysis for temperature trends and cardiovascular diseases hospitalization across twelve urban counties over the study period between 2005-2014, I found that there was no significant historical relationship between heat and cardiovascular diseases hospitalization rate. Not only did average maximum temperature displayed constant trends but the number of cardiovascular diseases hospitalization rates also showed a downward trend in all 12 urban counties. This study shows that urban counties in California have taken adequate measures within this study period to address cardiovascular health risks. However, in my study, I only used one exposure variable – temperature; hence, it might be misrepresentative of the magnitude of heat effects. Further research is required to project future heat-related cardiovascular health risks.
KW  - Urban Heat Island Effect (UHI)
