AB  - Contemporary livestock waste management in the United States is very inadequate compared to other international efforts. Other European countries incentivize more efficient composting methods, while United States lack policy reforms to push innovative technology. Although there exist new technology that can better our agricultural systems, there are many barriers such as lack of regulation and competition from other businesses that inhibit these innovations from being disseminated. Dirk Andrews invented a new aerobic composting technology that utilizes sulfur and ammonia found in livestock waste to compost the waste without emitting any Green House Gas and produces a new type of organic fertilizer that promises greater yields than conventional fertilizer. In order to see how this technology can properly be disseminated, I interviewed key figures in relevant fields to get their opinion on this product and the different pathways to diffusion. Although this innovation is necessary and can benefit many different people as well as the environment, it is still considered business disruptive to the oil industry and does not fit the criteria of organic by governmental organizations. However, there is still hope for this innovation as it is being adopted by different countries that have stricter regulations against ammonia. U.S. needs to reform their policy to help encourage environmental innovation and solve current issues like other countries as it is still behind other progressive nations that are moving towards more sustainable practices.
