U1  - PytowskiD_2017-page1.pdf
AB  - In recent years the increased complexity of electricity dispatch and usage has posed major problems for grid operators in California. With the exception of baseload generation, consumer behavior is the main factor in defining energy demand profiles. The primary goal of this study is to explore if and how domestic usage trends in per capita daily electricity demand change as solar penetration increases in residential areas. I determined the relationship between installed solar PV capacity and energy usage by comparing total energy use between areas of varying solar penetration across approximately 740 zip codes within the Pacific Gas and Electric Company (PG&E) service territory in California, over 5 years. I observed that average per capita electricity usage decreased significantly more in zip codes that saw a greater increase in installed solar PV capacity, over the years 2012-2016. Studies into the behavioral trends of consumers shed insight into developing more accurate demand projections, as they take into account the resulting cumulative impact of consumer habits as available energy technologies change and spread. The energy industry must refine its models of generation and demand, in order to adapt the management of the grid.
