AB  - Urban heat island (UHI) effect has become an increasingly concerning problem accompanying rapid global urbanization. UHI effect results in discomfort from warmer temperatures and poses public health hazards. UHI effect also contributes to increasing the rate of climate change, and thus, accelerates its affiliated detrimental effects. This study examined the effect of albedo, building floor area, wind speed, and solar irradiance on ambient temperature, which was used as a proxy for intensity of UHI effect. Data were taken from weather stations in the City and County of San Francisco and from Lawrence Berkeley National Lab. Results from simple ordinary least squares regression with small sample size revealed that building roof albedo was negatively associated with ambient temperature, and that solar irradiance was positively associated with ambient temperature. This suggests that broad adoption of high albedo roofs has the potential to mitigate UHI effect in dense cities. The study also points to a specific need for regulation of building roof design and materials at many scales – from the site to the city and regional level.
