PB  - University of California, Berkeley
UR  - https://www.ocf.berkeley.edu/~pkmendez/envsci/projects/2016final/LamW_2016.pdf
U1  - LamW_2016-page1.pdf
AB  - In this study, I estimated the life cycle greenhouse gas emissions of hydrogen fuel produced from both natural gas reformation and 33.3% of solar or wind electrolysis, and compared these outputs to the life cycle emissions of gasoline. Automotive exhaust emissions have a major impact on the global and local environment. Replacing petroleum-powered vehicles with clean alternative energy vehicles can reduce greenhouse gas (GHG) emissions. In order to understand the real-world impacts of using hydrogen as a transportation fuel in California, policymakers and companies need to be able to accurately evaluate the energy and emissions effects of hydrogen fuel and vehicle technology. Study methodology relied on using the California-modified Greenhouse Gases, Regulated Emissions, and Energy Use in Transportation (CA-GREET) model to evaluate well-to-wheels (WTW) energy and emissions impacts of various fuel-cell fuels. Examining results, hydrogen fuel cell vehicles (HFCVs) generated less life cycle GHG emissions, criteria pollutants, and consumed less fossil fuel energy than conventional vehicles. Moreover, when simulated renewable energy was used to produce hydrogen, lower upstream carbon emissions resulted – suggesting this approach might substantially lower overall transportation emissions. Thus, HFCVs can be a tool for achieving California's long-term goals of reducing GHG emissions and improving local air quality in the transportation sector.
