U1  - SchmiettE_2015-page1.pdf
AB  - Species distributions are changing faster than ever before, and these rapid changes have profound potential impacts on global ecosystems. Medusahead (Taeniatherum caput-medusae) is an invasive noxious weed that has caused significant economic and environmental damage to rangeland systems throughout the western United States. Due to medusahead’s aggressive colonization strategy, controlling its spread poses a serious challenge to rangeland managers. Medusahead is known to invade stands of cheatgrass (Bromus tectorum) and cohabitate; therefore cheatgrass’ distribution may help predict medusahead’s future spread. To investigate medusahead’s distribution and co-occurrence with cheatgrass, I compared three different species distribution models (SDMs): Generalized Linear Models (GLM), Generalized Boosted Models (GBM), and Maximum Entropy (MaxEnt). I evaluated these models based on two metrics: Area Under the Receiver Operating Characteristic Curve (AUC), and Cohen’s Kappa, to determine which modeling method produced the most accurate results. I then compared these SDMs of medusahead to co-occurrence models to determine if the inclusion of cheatgrass as an explanatory variable made the models more or less accurate. I also analyzed the importance of each environmental variable to determine which ecological constraint had the most impact on medusahead’s distribution model. Results showed that GBMs produced the most accurate results for medusahead distribution. Co-occurrence models increased accuracy in GLMs and GBMs, but had little effect on MaxEnt. Analysis of variable importance revealed that climate was the most important factor in medusahead distribution. The AUC values obtained from modeling indicate that these models are accurate enough to have real world management applications.
