AB  - Western burrowing owls (Athene cunicularia hypugaea) are designated as a Species of Special Concern in California as a result of being extirpated from much of its original range. The Breeding Bird Survey (BBS) and a survey by the Institute for Bird Populations (IBP) both measured the change in statewide owl population in 1991-1993 and 2006-2007 using different survey methods with help from citizen scientists. The BBS is conducted yearly and focuses on multiple bird species, while the IBP survey focused only on burrowing owls. No research has been done before on the effectiveness of these two surveys. To compare them, I first calculated owl distribution amongst regions and land classifications. I then used generalized linear models to determine change over time for the yearly BBS data. The Imperial Valley had the most owls in both surveys and both time periods, but many areas where owls were found in the IBP survey contained no owls in the BBS data. BBS routes where owls were found were limited to mainly lowland rangeland and agricultural land types. I found no significant trends for statewide population change in the BBS data, and regional population changes based on yearly data were very different from changes based on a single start and end point. My findings suggest that yearly, burrowing owl specific population surveys are needed to accurately predict change over time. This would be best accomplished by using citizen scientists to monitor historical breeding sites annually using uniform survey methods.
