AU  - Austin T. Jones
TI  - Engineering Subcellular Fluorescence for High-Throughput Microscopy Screening in Microbial Biofuels Production
PY  - 2013
PB  - University of California, Berkeley
UR  - https://www.ocf.berkeley.edu/~pkmendez/envsci/projects/2013final/JonesA_2013.pdf
U1  - JonesA_2013-page1.pdf
AB  - Engineering microbes for biofuels production demands precise control over subcellular localization, cell morphology, motility, and other such phenotypes that are only observable via microscopy. However, screening libraries of subcellular phenotypes using microscopy is currently inefficient and impractical. To bridge the phenotype of interest with the genetic identity of each microscopy-screened library member, we engineered microscopy barcodes (MiCodes) by targeting three fluorescent proteins (RFP, CFP, and GFP) to four organelles (nucleus, cell periphery, vacuolar membrane, and actin) in unique combinations within Saccharomyces cerevisiae. The MiCodes were optimized by selection of organelle shape and fluorescent protein expression creating visually distinct and identifiable cell signatures. The MiCode assembly was completed by iterative Golden Gate cloning, allowing for the engineering of large constructs with interchangeable parts. MiCodes were used to analyze interaction strength of a 36 member leucine zipper library using a bait and prey targeting assay to determine pairwise affinities and find orthogonal protein pairs. By coupling a unique fluorescent signature to each genotype present in a library, MiCodes enable high-throughput library screening using microscopy. MiCodes can be scaled to million member libraries with an automated screening method using script developed on two platforms: MatLab for image acquisition and CellProfiler for image analysis. Using photoactivatable fluorescent proteins and a confocal microscope increases the number of possible MiCodes and accuracy of MiCode identification, further propelling their application to large-scale libraries. MiCodes serve as a tool for synthetic biologists to increase the complexity and harness greater control of metabolic engineering for biofuels synthesis.
KW  - synthetic biology
KW  - leucine zipper
KW  - protein interaction
KW  - subcellular localization
KW  - library screening
ER  - 

TY  - THES
AU  - Jennifer B Jong
TI  - Identifying Xylan Synthesis Genes in Oryza sativa
PY  - 2013
PB  - University of California, Berkeley
UR  - https://www.ocf.berkeley.edu/~pkmendez/envsci/projects/2013final/JongJ_2013.pdf
U1  - JongJ_2013 -page1.pdf
AB  - With today’s growing concern for the environment, alternative sources of fuels are being investigated. Current fossil fuels are creating a net positive output of greenhouse gas emissions. Cellulosic biofuels are an excellent source of fuels due to its ability to be a carbon neutral fuel. The most viable source of cellulosic biofuels currently is from perennial crops. Cellulose is currently difficult to extract from cell walls due to its intertwining structure with hemicellulose, lignin and other unfermentable components. In order to maximize efficiency of fermentation, the amount of cellulose needs to be maximized while other components such as hemicellulose minimized. This can be achieved through an understanding of hemicellulose biosynthesis and gene regulation. IRX8, a gene encoding a protein that is proposed to synthesize the reducing end of xylan, a hemicellulose, was found in Arabidopsis. Rice has never proven to have this reducing end of xylan. However, the rice genome has a homolog—here named OsIRX8—which we hypothesized to be a functional equivalent of Arabidopsis IRX8. This study will test function of IRX8 and question the actual function of IRX8. This was done through complementation experiments. OsIRX8 was complemented into Atirx8 and tests were done to examine how well it complemented. Results show that growth rate, amount of xylan in the cell walls, xylem vasculature, and monosaccharide composition between the transformed plants and wild type are similar. This suggests that IRX8 does not function in creating the reducing end because the reducing end is not found in rice. Furthermore, the results identify IRX8 homologs in grasses as potential targets for improving bioenergy crops.
KW  - cellulosic biofuels
KW  - perennial feedstock
KW  - hemicellulose
KW  - rice
KW  - complementation experiment
