AB  - The National Environmental Protection Act (NEPA) was enacted in the early days of the environmental movement to ensure that development projects would not destroy the planet’s resources for future generations. However, the requirements in the legislation are often vague and it is up to researchers to determine effective scales and time frames for projects, making it possible that NEPA is ineffective in selecting the best option of many alternatives for the environment. I used a case study of Black-Crowned Night Herons (Nycticorax nycticorax) that had been relocated in Long Beach, California, in the late 1990s to address this possibility. At the time, several sites were considered as potential relocation sites. I looked at these sites today and used GIS to create suitability maps of each site to determine whether they would be considered well-suited to the herons nesting, breeding, and feeding requirements in the present day. I found that the sites had changed in ranking since they were first ranked in 1996, and the site that I determined was the best choice for relocation today was not the site chosen in the 1990s. This indicates that longer monitoring periods should be required to gain as much information about future changes to sites as possible, and post-hoc monitoring should also be required under NEPA and similar legislation to ensure that projects continue to meet their desired goals while still conserving the environment.
KW  - Geographic Imaging System (GIS)
KW  - suitability analysis
