AB  - The Western Grape Leafhopper (E. elegantula) can be a very destructive vineyard pest when in high enough concentrations. Though there is a lot known about how to manage them in vineyards during the growing season, not much is known about where they go during the overwintering phase of their life. I found out where these pests go during this period by sampling them with a D-Vac over a four month period to get rough estimates of what plants they are found on and in what numbers. E. elegantula was found on a number of plants such as California Buckeye and Ceanothus, they were found in very high densities on mint, which was the only statistically significant species after using a Two way Tukey HSD.
