U1  - CastroD_2012-page1.pdf
AB  - Phytophthora ramorum causes sudden oak death, a disease which has infected and killed several oak species in coastal California forests. Understanding of the disease's distribution is necessary for management. In this study, I examined data on more than one thousand coast live oak trees, to determine the relationship between infected oaks and two hosts. Within each of 107 randomly distributed plots in Redwood Regional Park, CA, I assessed coast live oak, madrone, and bay laurel for disease symptoms. I hypothesized that basal area of bay laurel trees had a significant effect on the presence of sudden oak death in coast live oak. I also hypothesized that basal area of madrone trees had a significant effect on the presence of sudden oak death in coast live oak. I found that bay laurel basal area or madrone basal area did not have a significant relationship with diseased coast live oaks in an abundance model (p=0.332, p=0.478). An association was only found between symptomatic coast live oaks and unhealthy bay laurel in the abundance model (p=0.0225). With proportion of symptomatic coast live oak on a plot, both bay and madrone basal areas had an association (p=0.00369, p=0.0198). Bay laurel has been considered to be the primary host of concern for propagation of P. ramorum in California forests. This study suggests that madrone could also be a significant host. Findings from my study can inform future research to minimize the spread of sudden oak death by assessing the potential of madrone as a threat to coast live oak.
KW  - bay laurel
