AU  - Neva Krieg
TI  - Utility Regulation: Barriers to Decoupling Electricity Sales from Revenue
PY  - 2009
PB  - University of California, Berkeley
UR  - NA
U1  - KriegN_2009_requested_nopub-page1.pdf
AB  - In 1982, in an effort to remove the economic incentive of investor-owned utilities to increase electricity sales and disincentive to implement energy efficiency programs, California became the first state to decouple sales from revenue as a means of electrical utility regulation. Since decoupling, California's per capita energy usage has remained relatively unchanged while the total United States' per capita energy usage has increased by fifty percent. Today the average Californian emits fifty-five percent less carbon dioxide and consumes one third less energy than the average American, indicating that energy efficiency programs have been successful in California. Although decoupling has been deemed successful by California utilities, California regulators, and energy insiders, it has not been implemented on a long-term basis outside of California. To best understand varying perspectives on decoupling, I interviewed academic experts, legislators, and energy industry insiders and analyzed responses. California utility experts believe lack of widespread implementation is largely due to the difficulty of implementing a new regulatory system. Experts agreed that a combination of decoupling and performance-based incentives are the most effective method of encouraging utilities to implement energy efficiency programs. This study provides a starting point for future research examining the successes and setbacks of decoupling in the United States.
