AU  - Eric Mertesdorf
TI  - The Ovicidal and Larvicidal Capabilities of Recent Reduced Risk Insecticides on Codling Moth Cydia pomonella
PY  - 2009
PB  - University of California, Berkeley
UR  - https://www.ocf.berkeley.edu/~pkmendez/envsci/projects/2009final/MertesdorfE_2009.pdf
U1  - MertesdorfE_2009-page1.pdf
AB  - I propose an analysis of two insecticides, Chlorantraniliprole and Methoxyfenozide on a major agricultural pest, Codling Moth, Cydia pomonella. Crop losses are derived from consumer expectancy of impeccable crops placing severe pressure upon farmers. Today the consumers expect perfect crops, including apples, resulting in severe financial losses for farmers. The continued application of insecticides including organophosphates has led to increased resistance and severe impacts upon non-target species. Reduced-risk insecticides limit impacts upon non-target species and the environment. Two more recent reduced-risk insecticides Chlorantraniliprole and Methoxyfenozide are promising ovicides (egg killers) or larvicides (larvae killers). I examined the application of each by dipping or spraying, prior to or after oviposition (egg deposition), with or without surfactants. After I dipped or sprayed each insecticide prior to or after oviposition, with or without surfactants, upon each individual apple, I then studied, analyzed and determined if efficacy of each improved. I discovered that both Chlorantraniliprole and Methoxyfenozide mortality rates averaged 50% or greater. I found Chlorantraniliprole was most effective when I dipped it prior to oviposition. Methoxyfenozide was most effective when I dipped or sprayed it after oviposition. Both insecticides targeted Codling Moth before damage occurred.
