AU  - Adam Regele
TI  - Managing Beijing’s Water Resources with Payment for Environmental Services
PY  - 2008
PB  - University of California, Berkeley
UR  - https://www.ocf.berkeley.edu/~pkmendez/envsci/projects/2008final/Regele_2008.pdf
U1  - Regele_2008-page1.pdf
AB  - In response to environmental threats to its primary water source, Beijing recently implemented new environmental management programs in the catchment of the Miyun Reservoir. Despite some success at addressing its deteriorating water quality, the Miyun remains vulnerable to excessive nutrient runoff and risks realizing the same deteriorated fate as Beijing’s previous water source, the Guanting Reservoir. The payment for environmental services (PES) model may represent a promising approach to addressing non-point source pollution in the Miyun. By aligning economic activities with environmental goals and increasing coordination between upstream and downstream communities, PES can address some of the key weaknesses in the Miyun’s current management program. Based on quantitative analysis, this paper finds that fertilizer reductions are a strong candidate for a PES scheme in the Miyun, although additional hydrological research to develop precise cost and benefit impacts is needed. China’s experience with the PES model illustrates some of its challenges, as well as providing lessons for its future application.
