AU  - Ryk Sheppard
TI  - Crypsis and Color Polymorphism in Theridion californicum (Araneae: Theridiidae)
PY  - 2008
PB  - University of California, Berkeley
UR  - https://www.ocf.berkeley.edu/~pkmendez/envsci/projects/2008final/Sheppard_2008.pdf
U1  - Sheppard_2008-page1.pdf
AB  - Color polymorphism is often observed in cryptic species, and is often related to escaping predation. Some of the most common cases of color polymorphism allow different individuals to match different types of backgrounds. In the less common case of apostatic selection, a small percentage of individuals look dissimilar from the common color morph, and are more likely to escape predation due to the predator’s inability to recognize the rare morphs. The spider Theridion californicum is both color polymorphic and cryptic. To determine if the specific color morph has any relation to the background, individual spiders were collected and compared to the leaves under which they were dwelling. The individuals were grouped by specific color morph, and by common themes, such as colors and patterns that were present through multiple color morphs. These categories were then compared to the amount of damage present on the leaves under which the individuals were residing. ANOVA was used to determine if there was any correlation betwixt certain color morphs and mean leaf damage. No statistically significant results were observed, and no color polymorph or group of morphs appeared to have any correlation with crypsis in this study. This supports the leading hypothesis that apostatic selective pressure is the main explanation for color polymorphism in T. californicum.
