AU  - Elizabeth Vu
TI  - Humpback Whale (Megaptera novaeangliae) Calling Behavior in the Stellwagen Bank
National Marine Sanctuary in the North Atlantic Ocean
PY  - 2008
PB  - University of California, Berkeley
UR  - https://www.ocf.berkeley.edu/~pkmendez/envsci/projects/2008final/Vu_2008.pdf
U1  - Vu_2008_no_pub-page1.pdf
AB  - Although humpback whales are traditionally thought to sing in their breeding grounds
for mating purposes, their song has also been recorded on their feeding grounds in the
Stellwagen Bank National Marine Sanctuary (SBNMS) in the northwest Atlantic Ocean. This
study investigates this phenomenon by determining when and how often these songs occur, how
long the song sessions last, and how song structure changes over time. The recordings from an
array of bottom-mounted recording devices (ARUs) in 2006 were used to investigate song
occurrence, song session duration, and changing theme structure over time. Song occurred more
frequently during the winter months while the longest song sessions occurred in spring and
winter. Song structure was dynamic from spring to autumn but reflected a return to original song
structure in winter. This study marks the beginning of analyses that may be done in SBNMS and
explores the role of humpback whale song heard outside of their traditional breeding grounds.
