TI  - Climate Change and its Effects on Plant and Consumer Stable Isotope Ratios in a California Grassland
PY  - 2007
PB  - University of California, Berkeley
UR  - https://www.ocf.berkeley.edu/~pkmendez/envsci/projects/2007final/Rudolph.pdf
U1  - Rudolph-page1.pdf
AB  - The global climate is rapidly changing due in part to anthropogenic activities. In addition to a general warming of the globe, annual precipitation levels in the Northern Hemisphere are predicted to rise. Increased precipitation has been shown to significantly affect plant and animal physiology and interactions. This study examines how an initial physiological response to increased precipitation in plants can affect feeding interactions and food quality in successive trophic levels. Grasshoppers (Camnula pellucida) and five of their food-plants (Eschscholzia californica, Rumex acetosella, Trichostema lanceolatum, Elymus glaucus, and annual grass dry litter) were sampled in manipulated rainfall plots in a large grassland meadow at the University of California’s Angelo Coast Range Reserve in Mendocino, California. I explore the effect that increased precipitation has on plant and herbivore interactions and the utility of stable isotope analyses for studying changes in trophic relationships in terrestrial food webs. Mass spectrometry indicated that 13C in plant tissues varied by watering treatment and not plant species type on the first collection date (July 7), but by the second collection date (July 30) 13C varied by plant species type and not by watering treatment. R. acetosella 13C composition varied significantly between control and spring rain treatments on the second collection date. All analyses of plant-herbivore pathways and 13C transmission efficiencies between trophic levels were found insignificant. These results contribute to our understanding of the effects that increased precipitation from climate change may have on species interactions.
