TI  - Environment versus Development: Assessing Environmental Predictions and Economic goals in the Community Mine Continuation Agreements for Western Province, Papua New Guinea
PY  - 2006
PB  - University of California, Berkeley
UR  - https://www.ocf.berkeley.edu/~pkmendez/envsci/projects/2006final/hiddenkisch.pdf
U1  - hiddenkisch-page1.pdf
AB  - Environmental damage caused by the Ok Tedi mine in Papua New Guinea resulted in the largest class-action lawsuit ever to reach Australian courts. In response to this, the mining company produced the Community Mine Continuation Agreements (CMCAs), a series of opt-out compensation packages to villagers in exchange for legal indemnity for all environmental pollution. The validity of the CMCA environmental predictions was assessed to determine whether these predictions were based on previous scientific research. Field interviews with community leaders investigated the role of economic development in influencing communities to sign the CMCA. The CMCA environmental predictions were found to severely understate the likely environmental effects of the mine, consisting largely of best-case scenarios. Analysis of the interviews found that the promise of economic development was a key factor in the signing of the CMCAs, and that the decision to sign the CMCA was more a resolution in favor of immediate compensation and incremental environmental damage instead of a highly uncertain court case. Differing degrees of community strength and environmental damage and along the river and access to mine benefits played key roles in determining the decision and motivations in signing the CMCAs. This study may have significance in an upcoming court case re-examining the legal validity of the CMCAs.
