AU  - Francesca Hopkins
TI  - Human Influences on the Carbon Cycle in Secondary Tropical Forests
PY  - 2005
PB  - University of California, Berkeley
UR  - https://www.ocf.berkeley.edu/~pkmendez/envsci/projects/2005final/Hopkins.pdf
U1  - Hopkins-page1.pdf
AB  - Recently it has been proposed that reforestation of tropical pasturelands may be an effective way to sequester atmospheric CO2, but the effects of re-forestation on the soil C pool are not well known. In addition, there have been few studies of the effects of climate change and N deposition on tropical soils. We used a long-term incubation experiment to investigate the effects of impending climate change and atmospheric N deposition on the soil C cycle of a reforestation chronosequence (0, 10, 30, 80 years) on tropical pastureland in Cayey, Puerto Rico. Based on measured soil CO2 effluxes and their 13C/12C isotope ratio, we observed a faster rate of C cycling in the soils of the active pastures (0y) relative to all ages of forest regrowth. The forest ages showed no significant differences among themselves. A 10°C warming led to significantly higher CO2 fluxes at all sites, indicating that future climate change could generate feedbacks to elevated CO2 and thus lead to additional warming. Addition of a NH4NO3 to approximate 50kg/ha/y N deposition had no measurable effect.
