AU  - Paul Schlegel
TI  - Community Garden Microclimate Analysis: Measuring The Effects of Evapotranspiration on Urban Climate Trends
PY  - 2005
PB  - University of California, Berkeley
UR  - https://www.ocf.berkeley.edu/~pkmendez/envsci/projects/2005final/Schlegel.pdf
U1  - Schlegel-page1.pdf
AB  - The climate of two gardens and one open space in West Oakland, CA were
monitored for three months in the Spring of 2005 for the purposes of this investigation.
Measuring air temperature and humidity every minute with HOBO H8 loggers, their data
was analyzed to show the extent vegetation affects the microclimates of the gardens.
Following the methods from previous studies of vegetation’s role in controlling air
temperature of Urban Heat Islands(UHI), a paired observation scheme compares each
garden against the control. To reduce compounding factors, eg- sky view factor, only the
measurements taken one hour before until one hour after sunset were analyzed. Each two
hour period was ranked for ideal sampling conditions(calm, sunny days) and divided into
two categories-before and after treatment of the control. From the regression equations,
slope was taken as the measure of cooling rate. The average cooling rate for each group
was then compared and statistically tested. Absolute humidity and air temperature
cooling rate increases demonstrate the degree to which evapotranspiration is responsible
for cooling effects. Quantifying this microclimate influence at sunset from direct
measurements, this experiment tests whether this method is able to quantify the cooling
rates and spatial persistence of those cooling differences.
