TY  - THES
AU  - Michiko Ishisone
TI  - Gas Flaring in the Niger Delta: the Potential Benefits of its Reduction on the Local Economy and Environment.
PY  - 2004
PB  - University of California, Berkeley
UR  - https://www.ocf.berkeley.edu/~pkmendez/envsci/projects/2004final/Ishone.pdf
U1  - Ishone-page1.pdf
AB  - Nigeria flares 17.2 billion m3 of natural gas per year in conjunction with the
exploration of crude oil in the Niger Delta. This gas flaring expends huge amounts of energy and
causes environmental degradation and disease. Even though oil has become the center of current
industrial development and economic activities, the links between oil exploration and
exploitation processes and the incumbent environmental, health, and social problems in oil
producing communities are not well known. This paper examines the potential benefits of a gas
flaring reduction on the local economy and environment, including the projected benefits of
utilizing associated gas. Also, the carbon monoxide level of ambient air was collected at four
villages, and other emissions related to flaring evaluated through related research. The results
show that the reduction of gas flaring can improve human health and the environment. This
paper concludes that the local livelihood in the Niger Delta can be significantly improved by
promoting a shift from flaring the associated gas to collecting it for use as a gaseous fuel and for
electricity generation. Although political feasibility poses a significant hurdle, economic and
energy initiatives need to be strongly integrated with other policies that promote development.
KW  - NA
KW  - NA
KW  - NA
KW  - NA
KW  - NA
ER  - 

TY  - THES
AU  - Todd Jones
TI  - Power and the Environment: Unpacking Land Use Development in San Diego
PY  - 2004
PB  - University of California, Berkeley
UR  - https://www.ocf.berkeley.edu/~pkmendez/envsci/projects/2004final/Jones.pdf
U1  - Jones-page1.pdf
AB  - Southern California, and the city of San Diego in particular, has become well known
for its application of a certain type of land use commonly known as ‘sprawl.’ This type of land
use or land development is widely recognized as particularly environmentally insensitive as it
tends to irreversibly alter large tracts of land, generally changing the landscape of a region.
Recently however, the city of San Diego has implemented programs and other land use policies
which have challenged its ‘growth-oriented’ reputation. Its system of land use procedures and
comprehensive environmental and conservation regulations have put San Diego at the fore of
what is often called ‘smart-growth’ planning. Yet, in 2001 a large development proposal called
Rancho Encantada was passed by the San Diego City Council. The project involves the
construction of almost 1,000 homes on the urban periphery. In this paper I attempt to explain the
Rancho Encantada project in its socio-political context. I seek to discover what characterizes the
context of land use and development (macro-scale environmental change) in San Diego, to
illustrate the effect of these characteristics on land use, and to identify the mechanisms of these
effects. I argue that a particular land use can be explained by the socio-political circumstances of
the land resource. I have developed a specific theoretical approach for this study which is
heavily influenced by work in the field of political ecology. I have organized the ‘socio-political
context/environment’ variable into an index of indicators comprising language, history, ideology,
and power relations. My results show that land use and development in San Diego is indeed
largely explained by specific environmental/contextual factors which are procedural, social,
political, economic, historical and linguistic in nature. This study shows as well that the socio-
political environment in San Diego comprises components which act to both constrain and
facilitate development interests. Finally, I offer a model for the use of open, undeveloped land
resources in San Diego. The model can work to show the general evolution of land development
on a particular scale, but only with the more detailed research which is needed to identify
mechanisms and how they are related, both of which may vary on a project-by-project basis and
certainly by locality.
