TY  - THES
AU  - Aariel Rowan
TI  - Barriers to Recycling in Castro Valley Public Schools
PY  - 2003
PB  - University of California, Berkeley
UR  - https://www.ocf.berkeley.edu/~pkmendez/envsci/projects/2003final/Rowan.pdf
U1  - Rowan-page1.pdf
AB  - In the spring of 2003, the Castro Valley Unified School District will implement a
district-wide waste diversion policy that will override the current recycling practices at each
school. The goals of this study are to measure the level of current recycling, the barriers to
further recycling, and to identify possible ways to overcome the barriers at each school in the
district. Data was collected through personal interviews with the recycling contact at each
school. Thirteen schools were sampled: nine elementary schools, two middle schools and two
high schools. The number of items recycled and the reported barriers varied among schools.
Possible reasons for this include the differences in personnel motivation and the amount of effort
each school has put into their recycling coordination. There are some interesting discrepancies
between what schools reported during my surveys and what the district office reported to the
California Integrated Waste Management Authority in their 2002 survey on waste diversion. As
well, the school district reported different barriers to recycling than were reported by the
individual schools. The difference in perceived barriers may simply be a product of different
perspectives.
