AB  - In this experiment the effectiveness of seedballs are studied as a direct seeding technique in native plant restoration at Muir Woods National Monument. Seedballs are broadcasted onto the restoration area where nonnative vegetations are dominant. I examined the germination success and the survivorship of seedball seedlings in grasses and forbs. However, unexpectedly rapid growth of nonnative grasses along with slow growth of seedball seedlings made the study design infeasible. Also, small and uneven sample sizes of seedball data were insufficient. The total number of plants in seedballs between March and April were not significantly different, yet comparisons with some standard measure or other restoration techniques are needed. Grasses, though fewer numbers of seeds were used, were more abundant both in March and in April than forbs.
