AU  - Andrea Apuy
TI  - Nitrogen Pathways in High Rate Pond Systems
PY  - 1999
PB  - University of California, Berkeley
UR  - https://www.ocf.berkeley.edu/~pkmendez/envsci/projects/1999final/KwakD_1999.pdf
U1  - KwakD_1999-page1.pdf
AB  - Methods for treating irrigation drainage water for the removal of toxins such as high concentrations of nitrogen and selenium have been a major environmental issue. Problems that arise from high concentrations of selenium and nitrogen in drainage water include health problems such as deformities and sterilization of nearby wildlife. One promising technology for irrigation drainage treatment is known as the Algal-Bacterial Selenium Removal System (ABSRS). The system is comprised of a high-rate pond (HRP) and a reduction unit that removes nitrate and nitrite and selenate. The purpose of this project was to attempt to increase the efficiency of the HRP in removing nitrate, which would lead to an increase in selenium removal by the reduction unit. This was accomplished by increasing the influent flow rate and by increasing the amount of CO2 injected into the HRP system. Weekly samples of the HRP influent and effluent were taken before and after flow rate and CO2 changes. The samples were evaluated for their nitrate and nitrite, ammonia, and total Kjeldahl nitrogen concentration. The data suggest that an increase in the flow rate and CO2 levels does not improve the efficiency of nitrate and nitrite removal. It is possible that there is a positive correlation between the increase in algal biomass with the increase in CO2. However, the increase in algal biomass does not increase the amount of nitrate and nitrate uptake by the system. Variables affecting the project include temperature, sunlight and acidity fluctuations due to weather. Future trials should control for these variables.
