AU  - Matt Bandel
TI  - Agroforestry Drainage Reuse Systems as a Potential Solution to Salinization in the San Joaquin Valley of California, Economic Sensitivity Analysis
PY  - 1999
PB  - University of California, Berkeley
UR  - https://www.ocf.berkeley.edu/~pkmendez/envsci/projects/1999final/ApuyA_1999.pdf
U1  - ApuyA_1999-page1.pdf
AB  - Salinization, the accumulation of salt in agricultural soils due to irrigation, is a growing problem in the San Joaquin Valley of California. This problem is compounded by poor drainage, resulting in high water tables that threaten to waterlog crops and salinate soils. An innovative technique using agroforestry has recently been developed to remediate this problem. It involves reusing agricultural drainage to irrigate successively more salt-tolerant crops, thus requiring less irrigation and producing less drainage. The salts collect in evaporation ponds rather than accumulating in the soils. This system has been in operation as a demonstration since 1987, and the data that have been collected suggest agroforestry is a sustainable system in terms of halting salt accumulation at tolerable levels and reducing drainage output. However, other questions must be answered regarding its economic feasibility, and the incentives to adopt such practices. Using simplified models of farm systems, the economic effects of adopting agroforestry can be compared to the economic effects of not adopting agroforestry. By varying the parameters of the model, it can be seen which parameters most strongly affect the economic incentives to adopt agroforestry practices for drainage and salinity management. Results suggest that agroforestry becomes an economically viable option only when long-term land and water quality issues are taken into consideration.
