AU  - M. Jamila Batchelder
TI  - The Potential for the Reintroduction of Rainbow Trout into Sausal Creek
PY  - 1999
PB  - University of California, Berkeley
UR  - https://www.ocf.berkeley.edu/~pkmendez/envsci/projects/1999final/BandelM_1999.pdf
U1  - BandelM_1999-page1.pdf
AB  - The degradation of California’s coastal streams has lead to a decline in populations of rainbow trout (Oncorynchus mykiss), particularly in its migratory form (steelhead trout). A major goal of the restoration project underway on Sausal Creek is to restore the historic rainbow trout population. It is unclear whether current conditions are sufficient to sustain a population. This study measured habitat characteristics critical to trout survival in two nearby streams that do have rainbow trout populations, Wildcat and Redwood Creeks. Measurements were taken of habitat types used by rainbow trout throughout their life cycle - adult habitat in the dry and wet season, spawning habitat, juvenile habitat, and transitional habitat. From these measurements, ranges of suitable values were developed. The same measurements were taken on the potential habitat in Sausal Creek. It was determined that most values fell within the suitable ranges. Values that did not fall within the ranges included water depth (below 0.4 meters in most study sites), numbers of boulders in spawning sites (below 2.5/m²), and insect abundance (low in overall abundance and EPT index value). Nine barriers to movement were also present. These characteristic were analyzed, and restoration techniques, such as adding boulders, modifying barriers, and adding erosion control devices, are suggested to bring these values into the suitable ranges. To manage for the issue of low water depth, restocking and restoration of the entire channel to the bay are recommended.
