AU  - Birgit Claus
TI  - The Role of Riparian Vegetation in Intercepting Nitrate
PY  - 1999
PB  - University of California, Berkeley
UR  - https://www.ocf.berkeley.edu/~pkmendez/envsci/projects/1999final/BatchelderMJ_1999.pdf
U1  - BatchelderMJ_1999-page1.pdf
AB  - Nitrate runoff from upland areas toward streams can be intercepted by vegetation in riparian zones, but the variability in uptake between species is poorly understood. I studied the effectiveness of various species in nitrate uptake in a simulated riparian zone, using a controlled greenhouse mesocosm experiment. Known concentrations of nitrate were applied to riparian channels, which contained plants of approximately equal age in coarse-grained sand of low organic content. Nitrate was extracted from soils using KCl to measure nitrate uptake amounts over time for Populus (cottonwood), Alnus (alder), Salix (willow), and Arundo (giant reed) spp. Root volume was measured to standardize nitrate uptake levels for variations in plant size. I found nitrate uptake values to be negative, indicating that NO3– levels in extracted soils were greater than the amount of nitrate applied, due to extraneous inflows. Species comparison of uptake was limited by these unknown flows, as changes in nitrate level could not be attributed to uptake by plants alone. Results suggest that NO3– sources are often more significant than expected, and therefore demonstrate a need to moderate and reduce fertilization of agricultural fields.
