AU  - Phillip Cornish
TI  - Measuring Post-Consumer Food and Paper Waste in the University of California-Berkeley Dormitory Dining Commons
PY  - 1999
PB  - University of California, Berkeley
UR  - https://www.ocf.berkeley.edu/~pkmendez/envsci/projects/1999final/ClausB_1999.pdf
U1  - ClausB_1999-page1.pdf
AB  - Dormitory dining common patrons at the University of California at Berkeley tend to waste a tremendous amount of food. While some of the pre-consumer food waste is collected and composted by Berkeley Worms, a non-profit student group, none of the post-consumer food and paper waste (plate scrapings and soiled napkins ) is targeted for waste diversion. In order to consider targeting this waste, Berkeley Worms must first have a good estimate of its quantity. The five dormitory dining commons included in this study combine to generate roughly 82 tons per semester. Additionally, this study sought to determine whether figures from one dining common were suitable to represent another. and whether figures from one meal type (i.e. breakfast or lunch) were suitable to represent another meal type. Per capita waste estimates were made by collecting and weighing a sample of waste and dividing this measurement by the number of patrons that contributed to it. Four pooled samples for each meal type at each of the five main dining commons were taken, for a total of 52 samples. Meal type and dining common means were calculated, analyzed, and then used to project tons per semester. Breakfast generated the least amount of food and paper waste (0.215 lbs/person), followed by lunch (0.307), brunch (0.373), and then dinner (0.336). This study suggests that in measuring these wastes, different meal types may need to be separated in order to produce accurate results. While the mean food waste generation of Units 1, 2, Clark Kerr and Foothill are all within a small range (0.292-0.342 lbs/person), Unit 3 is noticeably larger at 0.432 lbs/person. These results suggest that quantities produced in one dining common may be quite different than those produced in another. While more economic and energetic considerations should be done before deciding to compost this food waste, the soiled paper waste should be targeted immediately since it travels directly to the landfill. This study is relevant to other institutions wishing to understand their waste streams better, and has paved the way for numerous future studies.
