AU  - Jill J. De Haro
TI  - Knowledge of cryptosporidiosis and patterns of water use among high and low risk populations in health clinics around Berkeley California
PY  - 1999
PB  - University of California, Berkeley
UR  - https://www.ocf.berkeley.edu/~pkmendez/envsci/projects/1999final/CottrellC_1999.pdf
U1  - CottrellC_1999-page1.pdf
AB  - The largest Cryptosporidium parvum outbreak associated with drinking water occurred in Milwaukee, which sickened more than 400,000 people in 1993. Yet, traditional water treatment methods have been unsuccessful in removing this human pathogen. HIV- infected individuals and other immunocompromised individuals exposed to C. parvum through drinking water can suffer life-threatening effects. Therefore recommended guidelines are established to reduce their risk of cryptosporidiosis. A survey was conducted to assess the awareness of water drinking habits and knowledge of C. parvum among high and low risk populations who specifically seek HIV testing and other health care services in the city of Berkeley, California. 100 Questionnaires regarding water consumption patterns and knowledge of C. parvum were distributed to low risk populations of cryptosporidiosis at Clinic A, the Berkeley Public Health Clinic and to high risk populations at Clinic B, East Bay AIDS Center. Sixty-six surveys were returned ( n=35, Clinic A; n=31, Clinic B). High and low risk populations consumed primarily tap water followed by Brita-filtered and bottled water. Twenty-four percent of the low risk respondents had at least some knowledge of C. parvum, although no one considered themselves very knowledgeable. Sixty percent of the high-risk respondents had at least some knowledge and 17% were very knowledgeable. Respondents from both clinics initially found out about C. parvum from quite different sources. Physicians and AIDS related sources provide the most information in informing high risk populations while friends were the most important source for low risk populations. However, the news media plays a critical role for informing high and low risk populations. A vast majority considered information relating to C. parvum somewhat or very helpful. The majority of high risk respondents modified their water drinking habits and were highly concerned about cryptosporidiosis compared to low risk respondents. High-risk respondents were more aware of the benefits of in-sink filters and about using filtered water during food preparation than low risk respondents. Greater knowledge about C. parvum results in increased use of preventive measures Nonetheless, among high and low risk populations there is little awareness of secondary transmission routes. In all, high-risk populations who specifically seek HIV health care services are more aware of their water consumption habits in reducing cryptosporidiosis than low risk populations.
