AU  - Susan De Long
TI  - Selenium Uptake and Volatilization: Effects of Rhizosphere Microbes for Wildtype and Transgenic Brassica juncea
PY  - 1999
PB  - University of California, Berkeley
UR  - https://www.ocf.berkeley.edu/~pkmendez/envsci/projects/1999final/DeHaroJJ_1999.pdf
U1  - DeHaroJJ_1999-page1.pdf
AB  - Earlier studies found Brassica juncea to be an ideal species for phytoremediation of selenium contaminated soils. This plant species can convert inorganic selenium to volatile selenium, dimethyl selenide. The biological reduction of selenate to selenite was found to be a rate-limiting step. To overcome this barrier to optimum phytoremediation, Brassica juncea was transformed with the Arabidopsis APS1 gene for ATP-sulfurylase; the enzyme responsible for reduction of selenate to selenite. This study showed that overexpression of this gene resulted in 3-fold higher selenium volatilization rates from transgenic plants supplied with 50µM selenate. Transgenic plants also displayed higher tissue selenium concentrations than wildtype plants for both root and shoot tissues. The root concentrations were 5-fold higher than for wildtype plants. For transgenic plants supplied with selenite and L-selenomethionine, volatilization rates were reduced but tissue concentrations were equivalent to those of wildtype plants. In both wildtype and transgenic plants volatilization rates were significantly reduced when rhizosphere microbes were eliminated.
