AU  - Tim Flick
TI  - Casual Carpools, a Deeper Look
PY  - 1999
PB  - University of California, Berkeley
UR  - https://www.ocf.berkeley.edu/~pkmendez/envsci/projects/1999final/DeLongS_1999.pdf
U1  - DeLongS_1999-page1.pdf
AB  - Casual carpools are a fast growing phenomenon in the East Bay of the San Francisco Bay Area. The overall number of drivers is on the rise as is the number of pick-up spots. This was determined by observing ten pick-up spots in the East Bay during commute hours. On one hand surveys distributed at pick-up spots shows that casual carpools have removed 123 automobiles from the road. The amount of automobiles on the road was decreased by a combination of single occupancy drivers picking up passengers and others converting to being passengers. These surveys on the other hand show that if casual carpools were stopped 108 cars would be removed from the road. The fact that the number removed by the existence of casual carpools is greater than the number that would be removed if they stopped coupled with the fact that what people would do if the carpools were stopped forces people to predict the future suggest that these casual carpools are actually reducing congestion. Carpool lanes or HOV (high occupancy vehicle) lanes contribute to 63% of the people going into San Francisco on the Bay Bridge during commute hours. Casual carpools make up around 25% of these carpools so their impact on the commute and the environment is substantial.
