AU  - Michaelangelo Go
TI  - Determination of the Toxicity of Various Concentrations of Chloramine using Bioassays
PY  - 1999
PB  - University of California, Berkeley
UR  - https://www.ocf.berkeley.edu/~pkmendez/envsci/projects/1999final/FlickT_1999.pdf
U1  - FlickT_1999-page1.pdf
AB  - When water utility districts changed the disinfection method of tap water from chlorination to chloramination, the aim was to provide a high level of water treatment along with increased water standards. But another concern relates to the effect that chloramine has on fish in the water. Chloramine is toxic to fish, including fish that populate creeks and streams which can be influenced by tap water runoff that could be susceptible to changes in chloramine concentrations. From previous studies, it has been shown that an increase in concentration, along with an increase in exposure result in higher mortality in various test fish. The same should apply to fish that are found in creeks and streams, and this study aims to find the specific effects of differing concentrations on fish through bioassay testing. The mosquitofish, Gambusia affinis, was used as a bioassay subject to examine mortality when exposed to four concentrations of chloramine solutions at 2, 4, 12, and 15 mg/l. Higher concentrations of chloramine in test tanks resulted in higher mortality rates. Lower concentrations of chloramine produced little to no mortality, indicating a chloramine threshold concentration level of 12mg/l under which fish are tolerant when under. Rainbow trout, Oncorhynchus mykiss, proved more sensitive to chloramine whereby lower doses produced mortality rates higher than mosquitofish mortality rates. Solutions at 2, 4, 7, and 10 mg/l were used in the same bioassay experiments. Moreover, data on survival time and sub-lethal effects were measured for both species resulting in the observation that chloramine toxicity primarily affects respiratory functions but does not increase swimming activity. A jump in respiratory rates was observed for both species as concentrations surpassed 4 mg/l. Swimming activity remained constant through all concentrations. Mortality usually occurred within 4 days for mosquitofish and 48 hours for rainbow trout. The data collected indicate that fish mortality due to exposure to chloramine is dependent on factors such as the type of species, concentration, and exposure time. It supports the hypothesis that increasing concentrations lead to higher mortality for fish depending on species sensitivity. Within 5 days, the tendency moves towards 100% mortality for both species, especially in higher doses. Some environmental factors which may affect the concentration of chloramine delivered to fish in the wild such as dilution, evaporation, and fluctuation in chloramine effluent in the water. However, the data shows that the effect of chloramine is not identical for all fish. Fish such as mosquitofish, known to be more tolerant of poor water quality than Rainbow trout are more tolerable to the effects of chloramine, and this must be taken into account when ascertaining the overall toxicity of chloramine for fish.
