TY  - THES
AU  - David Han
TI  - Environmental Racism in Berkeley, California: 1940-1960
PY  - 1999
PB  - University of California, Berkeley
UR  - https://www.ocf.berkeley.edu/~pkmendez/envsci/projects/1999final/GoM_1999.pdf
U1  - GoM_1999-page1.pdf
AB  - Environmental racism influences the likelihood of exposure of environmental health risks to minorities while providing Whites with an edge to gaining a healthy physical environment. Environmental racism points specifically to the discriminatory siting of a large number of hazardous waste facilities and sites in many minority and specifically Black communities. While discriminatory siting of hazardous facilities provides one possible explanation of the occurrence of minorities in polluted neighborhoods, an alternative explanation is the influence of market dynamics forcing poor minorities into cheaper housing near industry plagued neighborhoods. During the 1940’s and the 1960’s, West Berkeley experienced numerous instances of blatant acts of housing discrimination towards minorities, especially Blacks. Practices such as block busting and redlining by banks were used to prevent Blacks and other minorities from entering wealthy White neighborhoods, and to constrain them to the poorer and polluted neighborhoods of West Berkeley. This paper concludes that discriminatory housing segregation policies, and not discriminatory siting policies, have probably had the greatest role in leading to the segregation of minorities, specifically Blacks, into the unhealthy neighborhood of West Berkeley.
