AU  - Jiwoon Jung
TI  - Heterotrophic Plate Count (HPC) Bacteria in Purged and Unpurged Water from Public Drinking Water Fountains
PY  - 1999
PB  - University of California, Berkeley
UR  - https://www.ocf.berkeley.edu/~pkmendez/envsci/projects/1999final/HanD_1999.pdf
U1  - HanD_1999-page1.pdf
AB  - One of the most important variables determining bacteria levels in drinking water at the tap is the concentration of disinfectant residuals. This depends on residence time of water since the concentration of disinfectant dissipates if the water sits longer in a service line. In public drinking water fountains, water may have a high residence time so that we might expect high natural bacteria caused by dissipation of disinfectant residual. In this study, samples from drinking water fountains in three public areas were collected to investigate Heterotrophic Plate Count (HPC) bacteria in purged and unpurged water. The study found that purged water (40 seconds) had significantly lower numbers of HPC bacteria as compared to unpurged water (zero seconds) (p<0.05). However, there was no evidence to correlate HPC bacteria counts with chlorine concentrations in unpurged water; HPC counts varied by sample location and drinking water fountain. Overall, the study concluded that if water was purged for 40 seconds, bacteria counts were greatly reduced regardless of the general chlorine levels and location of drinking fountains
