AU  - Roddy Khadem
TI  - Costs and Benefits of Genetically Modified Soy A Political-Economy Analysis
PY  - 1999
PB  - University of California, Berkeley
UR  - https://www.ocf.berkeley.edu/~pkmendez/envsci/projects/1999final/KaufmanCA_1999.pdf
U1  - KaufmanCA_1999-page1.pdf
AB  - This paper continues Susan Archer Mann and Jack Kloppenburg’s analysis of US agriculture by focusing on the recent technological advance in biotechnology, and in the soy crop in particular. Key components of Mann’s theory of the New Sociology of Agriculture, as well as Kloppenburg’s historical documentation, are synthesized in order to assess the costs and benefits of genetically-modified soy – both to the individual farmer and to society. These components are: 1) Dynamics of Commodification (Mann 1990), 2) Changes in the Means and Relations of Production (Kloppenburg 1987), and 3) Public Vs. Private Division of Labor (Kloppenburg 1987). Results indicate that genetic engineering has furthered the Commodification and, therefore, the capitalization of the U.S. soy crop. The development and implementation of bio-technology has been determined primarily by private interests, not public. Thus, the means of soy production have become more centralized under the control of agri-businesses and away from that of smaller-scale farms. Analysis indicates that while a limited number of agri-businesses are likely to benefit from genetically-modified soy, individual farmers and society at large are more likely to suffer – economically and environmentally. To mitigate these problems would require a greater role of public institutions in the development, implementation, and regulation of biotechnology.
