TY  - THES
AU  - Nina Kilham
TI  - Gully Development in the Claremont Creek Basin, Oakland, California: Investigating controls on hillslope erosion associated with diverted road runoff
PY  - 1999
PB  - University of California, Berkeley
UR  - https://www.ocf.berkeley.edu/~pkmendez/envsci/projects/1999final/KhademR_1999.pdf
U1  - KhademR_1999-page1.pdf
AB  - Excess sedimentation derived from gully scour has impaired the water quality ofstreams
throughout the Pacific Northwest. Often these gullies occur in association with roads, as inthe
east Oakland hills. To investigate how localized physical attributes influence gully formation
and development, mapping, characterization, and six volume assessments were made for the
Claremont Creek watershed (draining 1.2mi2 of north-east Oakland). Eleven gullies, mapped
on USGS 7.5 minutequadrants (1:24,000), arecharacterized by—percent soil exposed, dominant
vegetation type, slope and aspect. Additional parameters—type, size, percent flow obstructed,
distance of fall (shotgun), and the hillside position at which the culvert was placed-were used
to characterize thecondition of associated culverts. To estimate percent cover, a 2.2 nr (24 ft2)
wire mesh grid was placed atthegully head and percentages noted for sixstabilizing elements—
vegetation, boulders, emplaced structures, rocks, detritus, and large woody debris. Detritus is
excluded from the final analyses as it does not effectively conserve soil. A strong relationship
exists between the amount of exposed soil within the gully channel and the gully volume (r =
0.87 p=0.04). Gullies with 95-100% soil exposed lost 60 m3, 218 m\ and 62 m3 ofsoil (gullies
CC4, CC5, and CC7), while gullies with between 46-75% exposure only lost 4 m3 and 58.6 m3
of soil (gullies CC6 and CC11 respectively). Results indicate that boulders and roots are the
most abundant elements on average within these gully channels (13.7% cover). Interactions
between site conditions and road surface cover are also compared for paved and unpaved roads.
"Paved-road gullies" (PRGs) accounted for an average of41.53 ± 32.55 m3 ofsoil loss, while
unpaved "fire-trail gullies" (FTGs) accounted for an average 128.33 ±81.13 m3 of loss. All
gullies associated with paved roads were found to be larger in volume, however this relationship
was not statistically significant (p = 0.20). No gullies were observed in areas independent of
roads. Shotgun culverts and failed culverts also were important contributors to instability,
although protection at the gully head significantly reduced this effect. These relationships
suggest that small-scale controls may dictate gully development within a single watershed.
Monitoring gully development inthe future as a function of these controls, can thus provide a
means for assessing appropriate management techniques.
