AU  - Yonghwi Kim
TI  - Evaluating the Necessity for Cryptosporidium Regulation in California Drinking Water
PY  - 1999
PB  - University of California, Berkeley
UR  - https://www.ocf.berkeley.edu/~pkmendez/envsci/projects/1999final/KilhamN_1999.pdf
U1  - KilhamN_1999-page1.pdf
AB  - Drinking water is one of the most versatile means of transmitting diseases due to its wide availability. In recent years, Cryptosporidium has become water industry's main concern because of its serious health effects and the difficulties involved in treatment and detection. Unregulated for over 20 years since its discovery, the United States Environmental Protection Agency finalized the Interim Enhanced Surface Water Treatment Rule (IESWTR) in 1998 to regulate Cryptosporidium levels in drinking water. This study implemented a survey and contacted the water treatment facilities in Region 5 and 9 of ACWA, as well as examining the current regulation to determine the necessity for strengthening the IESWTR for California. The survey found that many facilities are incidentally treating for Cryptosporidium by using ozone and have been monitoring for it, but treatment for Cryptosporidium was not their primary concern. Upon examining the IESWTR, the study found that this regulation applies only to treatment facilities serving more than 10,000 whereas most of the outbreaks have occurred in smaller sized plants. The IESWTR uses turbidity to determine the effective removal rate of Cryptosporidium when no correlation between turbidity and presence of Cryptosporidium has been established. These flaws, combined with the belief of the treatment facilities that the water sources for California are very pure, led this study to conclude that it is necessary to strengthen the IESWTR for California. The study recommends ozonation to treat for Cryptosporidium and subsidization of use of point-of-use water treatment systems to provide safe drinking water to the public.
