AU  - Jen Kliris
TI  - An Estimation of Potential Exposures of Children to Highly Toxic Organophosphate and Carbamate Pesticides Through Inhalation Due to Drift from Agricultural Applications in the Metro Bakersfield Area, Kern County, California in 1995
PY  - 1999
PB  - University of California, Berkeley
UR  - https://www.ocf.berkeley.edu/~pkmendez/envsci/projects/1999final/KimY_1999.pdf
U1  - KimY_1999-page1.pdf
AB  - From 1991 to 1995, there was a 31% increase in overall agricultural pesticide use in California, largely in organophosphate and carbamate insecticides. Studies suggest that exposure to these chemicals may lead to numerous adverse health effects including long-term neurological problems. Drift of pesticide particles exposes residents of heavily populated nearby urban areas to highly toxic chemicals due to inhalation. Children are known to be especially susceptible to pesticide poisoning. This project investigates the potential exposure of children to nerve toxins through inhalation due to drift from agricultural applications in Kern county during 1995. The data show that the drift of toxic pesticides may be intensified by certain meteorological conditions. Air measurements of benomyl, a toxic organophosphate ranked 18th by toxicity, during February (a low application month) may have been considerably higher than the daily safe allowable limit for adults. This fact implicates other more toxic organophosphates used in Kern county during June, July and August (high application months), as potentially extremely harmful to residents of the heavily populated Bakersfield metro area, especially children. The study strongly suggests that the total adverse effects of highly toxic pesticides have been both understudied and underestimated. Further research is needed in order to assess the additive effects to human health due to inhalation of highly toxic agricultural pesticides applied in the vicinity of heavily populated areas. In addition, further investigation must address the potential compound effect due to inhalation, ingestion, and absorption.
