AU  - Alan Kwong
TI  - Sedimentation Due to Historic and Current Construction on Strawberry Creek
PY  - 1999
PB  - University of California, Berkeley
UR  - https://www.ocf.berkeley.edu/~pkmendez/envsci/projects/1999final/KwongA_1999.pdf
U1  - KwongA_1999-page1.pdf
AB  - Exposed soils associated with construction sites are highly prone to erosion necessitating the use of preventive measures to reduce soil loss during storms. The effectiveness of these measures is not well documented. Urban creeks like Strawberry Creek on the University of California, Berkeley campus wind up as the recipient of much of that sediment. This study gauges the effectiveness of erosion prevention at the many construction sites on the UCB campus. A follow up was conducted from a previous study of sedimentation in the creek to determine the lingering effects of construction sedimentation. In addition, the turbidity of the creek during rainfall was compared with a baseline to determine if current construction projects were adequately preventing soil erosion. The turbidity study found that the Haas Pavilion construction had a minimal effect on the turbidity of the creek during rainfall. The pebble count revealed that many of the sites correlated with previous studies but a closer look at the current data suggest that a contribution from the Haas site exist. The significance of the observed effects is unknown and is suggested for future studies.
