AU  - Zaylin Lalji
TI  - The Impact of Vegetation on Psychological Health
PY  - 1999
PB  - University of California, Berkeley
UR  - https://www.ocf.berkeley.edu/~pkmendez/envsci/projects/1999final/LaljiZ_1999.pdf
U1  - LaljiZ_1999-page1.pdf
AB  - People are increasingly acknowledging the value of nature for improving psychological health. This project illustrated how the level of vegetation in outdoor spaces affected people’s perceptions of aspects of their short-term psychological health on the U.C. Berkeley campus. This was tested using a survey study at three sites on campus which varied in degree of vegetation (~0%, 50%, and 100%). The four indices used to measure psychological health were personal comfort, social bonding, self-esteem, and mental stimulation. This study also determined how the impact of vegetation on psychological health is related to gender (a person’s biological identity as male or female) and gender identity (one’s self-perceived degree of masculinity or femininity). Furthermore, the project investigated the effect of different sources of self-esteem (ranging from completely internal to completely external) on self-esteem, one of the indices used to measure psychological health. The variation of the impact of sources of self-esteem was analyzed according to differences in gender and gender identity. Results showed that vegetation improves people’s temporary psychological state in an outdoor space. This study also found that women reacted more strongly than men to this effect and that there were greater correlations between gender identity than gender with the four indices used to measure psychological health.
