AU  - Meridith Lear
TI  - Lead Abatement Policy in the City of Berkeley
PY  - 1999
PB  - University of California, Berkeley
UR  - https://www.ocf.berkeley.edu/~pkmendez/envsci/projects/1999final/LearM_1999.pdf
U1  - LearM_1999-page1.pdf
AB  - Despite regulations reducing allowable concentrations of lead in paint, lead poisoning resulting from the inhalation or ingestion of lead-based paint particles persists as a major environmental hazard. The only regulations which aim to directly protect the Berkeley public from improper lead-paint abatement activities were set by the California Department of Health Services, and this department does not actively enforce these regulations in the city of Berkeley. The objective of this report is to assess the city of Berkeley’s need to oversee and enforce lead-based paint removal regulations through the implementation of a lead abatement plan. To determine the potential for lead poisoning from paint in the city of Berkeley, toxicological effects of lead, housing-stock statistics and current city policies were taken into account. In Berkeley, 98% of the housing units are likely to contain paint with levels of lead that pose a threat of lead poisoning to human health. Lead poisoning is an environmental illness which is preventable, since the causes of lead poisoning are well-understood as are the means of eliminating them. Taking into account the extreme physiological impacts of lead poisoning, along with the high proportion of high-risk housing stock, formal enforcement procedures for lead paint abatement would greatly protect the health of the people who reside in Berkeley.
