AU  - David Levitan
TI  - Trends in Lead Poisoning and Lead Source Exposure in Hispanic Children in California
PY  - 1999
PB  - University of California, Berkeley
UR  - https://www.ocf.berkeley.edu/~pkmendez/envsci/projects/1999final/LevitanD_1999.pdf
U1  - LevitanD_1999-page1.pdf
AB  - A retrospective cohort study was completed analyzing the differences in blood lead levels (BLLs) among Hispanic children based on (1) residence time in the US and (2) source of lead exposure. The study was conducted using data from the RASSCLE database maintained by the Childhood Lead Poisoning Prevention Branch (CLPPB) of the California Department of Health Services. Hispanic children between the ages of one and five that met case criteria of lead poisoning for the state of California were analyzed to determine any trends in lead poisoning in California’s Hispanic child population. Results showed residence time in the US to be a small but significant determinant towards the elevation of BLLs, increasing mean BLLs by just over 1 microgram/ deciliter (ug/dl). Home remedy exposure was found to be the most important single determinant of childhood lead poisoning in Hispanic children, and varied greatly according to residence time in the US. In addition, an analysis was conducted correlating socioeconomic data from the 1990 US Census with all children in the RASSCLE database that had been tested for lead poisoning, stratified by case status, zip code, and ethnicity. Socioeconomic variables such as child poverty and median household income were found to be closely correlated with increases in childhood lead poisoning. Overall, identifying traditional Mexican home remedies as a serious hazard for lead poisoning and phasing out residential housing with paint made before 1978 may help reduce the prevalence of lead poisoning in Hispanic children in California.
