AU  - Lotina S. Lin
TI  - Effect of pH on Chlorine Residual Decay in Chloramine-Treated Water
PY  - 1999
PB  - University of California, Berkeley
UR  - https://www.ocf.berkeley.edu/~pkmendez/envsci/projects/1999final/LinLS_1999.pdf
U1  - LinLS_1999-page1.pdf
AB  - Traditionally, our drinking water has been disinfected with chlorine to protect us against water-borne diseases. However, chlorine is not an ideal disinfectant because it forms harmful disinfection by-products and has low residual stability. As a result, many water companies are switching to using chloramine, a common alternative. Chloramine, a combination of chlorine and ammonia, does not have the problems that chlorine does, but its germicidal potency is also much weaker than chlorine. Utilities, therefore, must run tests and experiments, before a conversion, to find how best to implement the process into their existing operations. The San Francisco Water Department is currently undergoing this process. One component of the chloramination system that they are interested in studying is how variations in pH can affect the stability of their chloramine residuals. This was examined by treating their chlorinated samples with ammonia and then observing them under different pH conditions. It was found that hydrogen ions indeed do play a role in determining the decay rates of their chloramine residuals. In fact, the optimum pH range for the implementation of their chloramination system was found to be between 8.5 and 9.0. Further research, however, in the form of pilot tests, are needed for a more thorough and beneficial study.
