TI  - An Assessment of Environmental Education Programs in the San Francisco Bay Area through Teacher and Student Perspectives by
PY  - 1999
PB  - University of California, Berkeley
UR  - https://www.ocf.berkeley.edu/~pkmendez/envsci/projects/1999final/MadhavanH_1999.pdf
U1  - MadhavanH_1999-page1.pdf
AB  - Environmental education has become a key tool for distributing information and promoting awareness to the public regarding environmental issues. This study evaluates the success of environmental education programs in the S.F. Bay Area by analyzing teacher and student ratings of current programs. I defined program success as positive change in student knowledge of the environment, student attitude towards the environment, and student behavior towards the environment. Student surveys and teacher interviews were used to assess program success. The study also compared teacher and student response to identify similarities and differences in attitudes and draw conclusions regarding the future success of programs. Surveys and interviews provided useful information on the status of current programs and on how to improve these programs to increase success. Overall, teachers felt there were great changes in student knowledge and attitude yet did not feel there were notable changes in student behavior. In comparison, student response indicated changes in behavior as well as knowledge and attitude. Private school students responded more favorably to environmental programs than public school students on all three levels. Thus, this study determined the effectiveness of current environmental education programs by analyzing and comparing teacher and student response to find that current EEP are successful in terms of causing changes in students, yet need improvements to ensure future success.
