TI  - The Role of Parks in Environmental Education: A Study of the San Francisco Presidio's Outdoor Educational Program
PY  - 1999
PB  - University of California, Berkeley
UR  - https://www.ocf.berkeley.edu/~pkmendez/envsci/projects/1999final/McFaddenB_1999.pdf
U1  - McFaddenB_1999-page1.pdf
AB  - This study identifies and examines the essential elements of effective public, outdoor, environmental education programs in parks. This project was designed to develop a set of recommendations, that will enable the San Francisco Presidio to establish a distinct set of guidelines and parameters to be used in the development of future programs. As an urban National Park, the San Francisco Presidio offers a unique opportunity for effective public education about nature and the environment. Surveys distributed to visitors of the Presidio and three East Bay Regional Parks (Tilden, Crabcove and Sunol) served as an integral part of a local study to determine interest in environmentally related topics. They also served to determine how the opinions of program participants at the Presidio differ from those of parks that are more traditional. Program participants throughout the parks expressed through this survey an interest in learning about nature, sustainability and environmental issues. Relative to East Bay Park visitors, Presidio visitors found cultural history to be a more important aspect of the educational programs, but they were, overall, less confident that adequate focus was being given to other subjects, such as animals, trees, plants and environmental issues. The findings of this study suggest that if the appropriate steps are taken, under the proper planning and management, the San Francisco Presidio could serve as a model of sustainability and environmental education for other National Parks.
