AU  - John H. Peng
TI  - The Chemical Composition of Soda Lake in the Carrizo Plains Natural Area and the Precipitation of Salts at Low Natural Temperatures
PY  - 1999
PB  - University of California, Berkeley
UR  - https://www.ocf.berkeley.edu/~pkmendez/envsci/projects/1999final/PengJH_1999.pdf
U1  - PengJH_1999-page1.pdf
AB  - Soda Lake is a terminal hypersaline lake in the Carrizo Plains Natural Area in the southern San Joaquin Valley. Salinity is approximately 90 ppt. The ionic composition of the lake consists of high cation concentrations of Na+ (36,180-53,220 ppm) and Mg+2 (5512- 7132 ppm) and high anion concentrations of Cl- (65,000 ppm) and SO4-2 (24,000 ppm). Sampling of the lake water was taken on three dates in the months of November and December in 1998 with each date approximately 18 days apart. Precipitation and crystallization of salts on the lake bottom were observed on 5Dec and 23Dec when natural temperatures fell below 6.1°C and 4.5 °C respectively. Laboratory tests show a precipitation threshold that varies with both temperature and salinity. The temperature threshold where precipitation occurs has a linear and positive correlation with salinity (correlation = 0.968) according to the equation: Precipitation Temperature Threshold (°C) = 0.1907 (salinity in ppt) – 8.893. Molarity ratio comparisons based on the ion concentrations of the lake water samples show that the crystal formation observed on 5Dec and 23Dec was composed mainly of the compound Na2SO4, a constituent of the minerals thenardite and mirabilite. Because Na2SO4 precipitates from solution as a function of the temperature and salinity of the lake water, the seasonal occurrence of salt crystallization over the lake bottom can be predicted using historical records of rainfall and average temperature.
