AU  - Ilana Stout
TI  - Factors Affecting the Success of Amphibian Recovery Programs
PY  - 1999
PB  - University of California, Berkeley
UR  - https://www.ocf.berkeley.edu/~pkmendez/envsci/projects/1999final/StoutI_1999.pdf
U1  - StoutI_1999-page1.pdf
AB  - Data on amphibian recovery programs are limited and have yet to be compiled. This study compiles information on reintroduction and recolonization programs with emphasis on factors that affect differing lifestages at reintroduction. A survey of protocols in projects was conducted to determine factors correlated with reestablishment of populations. Literature review and interviews with persons involved in recovery projects suggest that programs that promote local recolonization have higher success rates than reintroduction programs and that non-native predators are a major problem for both recolonizations and the early lifestages in reintroduction. I examined the impact of an introduced species of crayfish(Pacifasticus lennisculus)on Pseudacris regilla, an anuran native to creeks in the east San Francisco Bay region. Predation experiments exposed P. regilla eggs and two sizes of larvae to P.lenniculus. Crayfish preyed upon recent hatchlings more than eggs or fully-grown larvae. Predator avoidance in large(1-2 month old) larvae was evident in changes in habitat use. Larger larvae spent more time on the walls of artificial pool habitats than small larvae. Larger larvae also showed higher concentrations along the walls following introduction of a crayfish. Small(<1 month old) larvae remained on the floor of pools following crayfish introduction. Implications of predator avoidance behaviors in lifestage for reintroduction are discussed.
