TI  - The Ecological Impacts of the Chinese Mitten Crab, Eriocheir sinensis, an Invasive Species in the San Francisco Bay Area
PY  - 1999
PB  - University of California, Berkeley
UR  - https://www.ocf.berkeley.edu/~pkmendez/envsci/projects/1999final/TangI_1999.pdf
U1  - TangI_1999-page1.pdf
AB  - The Chinese mitten crab, Eriocheir sinensis, is a recent invader of San Francisco Bay and offers an opportunity to study the process of invasion early in its introduction. This paper assesses the habitat preference of the adult and juvenile Chinese mitten crab and study its impacts on the native flora and fauna in small streams. The crab’s impact on the Signal crayfish, Pacifastacus leniusculus, reveals that there may be some competition for resources since they share the same habitat. No adult crabs were found north of site 1 at the Boyes Boulevard cross street, approximately 15 km upstream of Sonoma Creek. Similarly, only one crayfish was found downstream of this site. This may indicate a competition of resources between the two species and competitive displacement of crayfish. The substrate size preference test conducted on juvenile crabs showed a marginal preference for rocks less than 2 cm long and packed closely together. These preferences may indicate that the juveniles may be able to find more substantial shelter with smaller particle sizes. Furthermore, the juveniles preferred deeper water depths of at least 21-30 mm.
