AU  - Pei-hsuan Wu
TI  - Volunteers at U.C. Berkeley: Motivations and Characteristics
PY  - 1999
PB  - University of California, Berkeley
UR  - https://www.ocf.berkeley.edu/~pkmendez/envsci/projects/1999final/WuP_1999.pdf
U1  - WuP_1999-page1.pdf
AB  - In search of more volunteers in this time of social and environmental problems,
this study examines characteristics and motivations of volunteers at three volunteer
organizations and an annual service event. The results raise five major points: 1) that women
outnumber men, and more research should be given to attracting men; 2) early exposure to
volunteerism correlates strongly with a future in volunteerism; 3) motivations are linked with
neither religion nor income; 4) the long-term volunteers surveyed in this study rate their
reasons for volunteering more highly than the volunteers from a short-term volunteering
activity; and 5) positions that attract volunteers help volunteers to broaden their horizons and
have a recognized positive social value. This project is limited by the small sample and
response rate, but the data are offered as the outcome of a small pilot study that should be
continued to form stronger statements about volunteerism.
