TI  - The Economics of PV Technologies: A Hypothetical Case Study at UCB
PY  - 1998
PB  - University of California, Berkeley
UR  - https://www.ocf.berkeley.edu/~pkmendez/envsci/projects/1998final/ChenY_1998.pdf
U1  - ChenY_1998-page1.pdf
AB  - Photovoltaic (PV) systems currently produce clean renewable energy, though at a higher cost than utility power. New technologies of PV systems, such as building integrated photovoltaics (BIPV) systems help close the price gap between PV and utility electricity. In the urban environment, where the majority of electricity is consumed, there is a growing market for BIPV systems. In certain geographic locations the economic feasibility of solar applications approaches that of utility power. The University of California at Berkeley campus is a prime site for testing the feasibility of this type of solar application due to the favorable climate and current tax incentives and rebates offered by the government for solar energy applications. A financial analysis was completed for a hypothetical two megawatt BIPV system on the campus. The lifecycle unit cost for this system would be $0.049 per kilowatt-hour (kWh), compared to the average $0.051 per kWh the University paid for electricity last year.
