TY  - THES
AU  - Renee Azerbegi
TI  - Mexico, the United States, and Solar Energy: Comparing Impediments and Solutions to Photovoltaic Applications
PY  - 1998
PB  - University of California, Berkeley
UR  - https://www.ocf.berkeley.edu/~pkmendez/envsci/projects/1998final/AllenL_1998.pdf
U1  - AllenL_1998-page1.pdf
AB  - Photovoltaic cells can be used in a wide variety of applications for production of electricity. They rely on sunlight, have little impact on the environment, and can be used as independent power sources, as electricity connected to the electricity grid, or in combination with other sources. Cost-effective markets for photovoltaic systems (PVS) differ in size and application in developed and developing countries due to differences in electricity costs and in the size of populations without access to the electricity grid. This study compares usage of PVS in Mexico to usage in the United States with a focus on the states of Arizona and Sonora. Data was gathered from numerous sources and interviews of professionals in the solar energy field in both countries were conducted. Barriers and solutions to use of PVS have been identified in decreasing order as financial, sociocultural, infrastructural, institutional and technical. Although barriers to photovoltaics are similar, the degree to which the various barriers reduce market penetration vary greatly, as do the opportunities for further development of photovoltaic applications. Due to identified cost-effective PVS markets and the size of these markets, it is recommended that PVS be expanded for on-grid applications in Arizona and off-grid applications in Sonora. Nationally, Mexico should increase its off-grid PVS supply infrastructure and financing options, manufacture its own PVS, and incorporate users to a greater extent in its government led promotion of PVS. The United States should continue to research and develop the technical components of PVS, identify the most cost-effective markets, and expand its on-grid PVS supply infrastructure. The US government should encourage on-grid PVS via tax credits, financing options, incorporation of environmental externalities, and information dissemination.
