TI  - PM10 vs. PM2.5: Beginning the Search for a Correlation
PY  - 1998
PB  - University of California, Berkeley
UR  - https://www.ocf.berkeley.edu/~pkmendez/envsci/projects/1998final/AzerbegiR_1998.pdf
U1  - AzerbegiR_1998-page1.pdf
AB  - On July 16, 1997, the Environmental Protection Agency (EPA) adopted a new group of National Ambient Air Quality Standards (NAAQS) to control airborne particulates of less than 2.5 microns (μm) diameter (PM2.5) . This report quantifies the relationship between PM2.5 and currently available PM10 (particles smaller than 10 μm in diameter) ambient concentration measurements as well as site-specific meteorological and seasonal data. Bay Area Air Quality Management District (BAAQMD) dichotomous sampler readings from Livermore, Concord, and San Jose were statistically analyzed and regressions were fit to the data to explain variations in the ratio of PM2.5 to PM10 concentrations (Fine/Total ratio). Strong correlations were found between this ratio and temperature, average wind speed, maximum wind speed, relative humidity, and total PM10 levels. In addition, seasonal analysis indicates that while fine particles make up the significant part of PM10 in the winter months, coarse (d > 2.5 μm) particles make up the bulk of PM10 in the summer.
