UR  - https://www.ocf.berkeley.edu/~pkmendez/envsci/projects/1998final/BeizaieR_1998.pdf
U1  - BeizaieR_1998-page1.pdf
AB  - Hydrocarbon-contaminated soils planted with Avena barbata (rhizosphere soil), were able to selectively enrich for degrader organisms as compared to unplanted (bulk) soils. The role of hydrocarbon presence, hexadecane and phenanthrene, was examined in order to determine if they were a necessary component in the selection of hydrocarbon degraders. In non-contaminated soils planted with Avena barbata, selective enrichment of hexadecane and phenanthrene degraders was not observed. Rhizosphere to bulk soil population ratio (R/ S ratio) data from non-contaminated soils suggests that hexadecane and phenanthrene presence is required for selective enrichment of microbial degraders in rhizosphere soils.
