PY  - 1998
PB  - University of California, Berkeley
UR  - https://www.ocf.berkeley.edu/~pkmendez/envsci/projects/1998final/BernabeKG_1998.pdf
U1  - BernabeKG_1998-page1.pdf
AB  - The need for feasible renewable energy systems to replace the environmentally damaging fossil fuel combustion plants has inspired creative inventors to develop novel energy generating technologies. One such design is the Vehilectrical Power System, a vertical axis turbine mounted in the median of highways which will harness the combined bi-directionally induced winds of traffic flow. This study contributed to the determination of the feasibility of VPS by obtaining direct wind measurements from the median barrier. The data were analyzed, and an economic assessment of the system’s initial maximum capital investment was determined to be $280 per 20 ft segment of median barrier. Under the conditions of the study, the VPS was not found to be economical in the current energy market due to high operation and maintenance costs, low energy output, and low wind velocities generated on the highway.
