TI  - University of California Residence Hall Waste Composition Analysis
PY  - 1998
PB  - University of California, Berkeley
UR  - https://www.ocf.berkeley.edu/~pkmendez/envsci/projects/1998final/BrownE_1998.pdf
U1  - BrownE_1998-page1.pdf
AB  - The level of recyclable materials found in a refuse stream is widely assumed to decrease with the availability of recycling locations. This project examines the overall composition of the waste stream of selected residence halls at the University of California at Berkeley, and examines whether there is a significant relationship between the number and placement of recycling locations and the percentage of refuse that is recyclable. Sixteen samples of refuse were sorted into nineteen material categories. The overall percentage of recyclable material in the refuse was 38.28%. The sample sites were divided into two groups based upon the availability of recycling locations at each site. The mean percentage of recyclable material in the refuse of the first group was 16.15%. For the second group the mean was 21.64%. When analyzed using a t-test at a 0.90 confidence level these results show that there is a statistically significant correlation between the number of recycling locations and the percentage of recyclable material in the refuse.
