TI  - Using Animal Sentinels to Protect European Freshwater Habitats
PY  - 1998
PB  - University of California, Berkeley
UR  - https://www.ocf.berkeley.edu/~pkmendez/envsci/projects/1998final/BucknellT_1998.pdf
U1  - BucknellT_1998-page1.pdf
AB  - Techniques that monitor invertebrates and fish in fresh water rivers and lakes are the most effective means for assessing an ecosystem's health. In this thesis, I explain Europe's need for standardized aquatic monitoring and present the most cost-effective and pragmatic biomonitoring methods available for implementing an effective monitoring process throughout the continent in order to successfully implement entire policies. The specific techniques that I propose include macroinvertebrate identification within water bodies in order to assign each family a score based upon their relative sensitivity to pollution. Established indices such as the British BMWP that correlate these scores are useful and cost-effective methods for comparing the relative amount of water pollution among rivers. In addition to invertebrate sampling, I propose biomonitoring techniques that examine the tissue samples of fish in order to assess physiological damage caused by the many different types of xenobiotics. By analyzing the fish tissues at the molecular level, one can measure aquatic pollution's effect on the immune system, metabolic energy, reproductive capabilities, and overall fitness levels of a fish population. All of these biomarking tests are extremely useful since they can explain the effects of pollution at the level of individuals before more irreversible symptoms begin to affect ecosystems at the community level.
