TY  - THES
AU  - Crystal J. Chamness
TI  - Flooding to Reduce Selenium Toxicity
PY  - 1998
PB  - University of California, Berkeley
UR  - https://www.ocf.berkeley.edu/~pkmendez/envsci/projects/1998final/CaffeyS_1998.pdf
U1  - CaffeyS_1998-page1.pdf
AB  - Selenium concentrations in some wetlands within California have been measured well above EPA standards for the protection of wildlife resulting in mutations and the reduction of wildlife populations. Wastewater treatment facilities for selenium in agricultural runoff, the primary transport mechanism of selenium to wetlands, are currently being developed. However, wetlands already contaminated with selenium from agricultural wastewater need be managed or remediated to reduce the dissolved, toxic form of selenium. Reduction processes during flooded conditions can transport this form of selenium to the sediments, while oxidation processes during dry conditions can remobilize it to the water column. I evaluated the rates of selenium oxidation in wetland sediments with different total selenium concentrations during a simulated dry season to estimate the rate at which wetlands reach toxic levels during oxidizing conditions. I found that selenium oxidation is a first order rate reaction whose rate of oxidation or k-constant is independent of initial selenium sediment concentrations. This oxidation rate formula, which is a function of initial selenium sediment concentrations and the time of drying, was used to accurately model the increase in dissolved selenium concentrations upon re-flooding. Ideally, and with further field research, this formula could be used by wetland management to determine periodic flooding regimes which will minimize selenium toxicity in contaminated wetlands. Additionally, I identified the role of organic selenium in increasing dissolved concentrations during drying, thereby aiding in the discussion of the proper disposal regiment for selenium rich plant matter in constructed wetlands used for wastewater treatment.
