AB  - Columbian black-tailed deer (Odocoileus hemionus columbianus) have proliferated in the urban residential neighborhoods of El Cerrito hills due to the abundant food available and the absence of predators. Their growing numbers, however, are threatening human health and safety. This study assesses the dietary quality of these urban deer by comparing their fecal nitrogen with that of deer in natural areas. The study did not find any differences in forage quality between the deer in the two areas. The average percent nitrogen difference in the fecal samples of the two areas was always less than 0.2%, which is lower than found in previous studies conducted by Gogan and Barrett (1995) and Massey et al. (1994). Low nitrogen content may be related to the difference in precipitation each area received during the study year. Possible solutions of controlling the deer population by means of limiting preferential food and nitrogen-rich food to the deer are also discussed.
