TY  - THES
AU  - Yarnie Chen
TI  - The Invasion of the Brown Tree Snake (Boiga irregularis) on Guam: The Use of Barriers to Control Population Expansion
PY  - 1998
PB  - University of California, Berkeley
UR  - https://www.ocf.berkeley.edu/~pkmendez/envsci/projects/1998final/ChauM_1998.pdf
U1  - ChauM_1998-page1.pdf
AB  - In this technological era of frequent international travel, human-assisted
migrations of invasive species are increasing and can sometimes create biological catastrophes
as opportunities for such unwanted guests expand. Combating these proliferating invasions of
exotic species can be costly and arduous, but it is not impossible. The invasion of the brown
tree snake, Boiga irregularis, on Guam exemplifies the range of problems caused by a single
invading species. The snake has decimated Guam's avifauna population where nine of the
twelve native forest birds became extinct, as well as created numerous economic problems and
adverse ecological impacts. Efforts to control and manage B. irregularis have slowly
moderated the problem, but the brown tree snake is still a major threat to Guam's ecosystems
and particularly to nearby islands where it is not yet present. Complete eradication of B.
irregularis has been considered infeasible and therefore the alternative would be control
methods to maintain the snake population on Guam and prevent further introductions to other
islands. In particular, construction of barriers may keep snakes out of cargo areas and airports
where dispersal to other islands are likely to occur. Testing the adequacy of two polyvinyl
barriers of different heights (1.2 m and 1.5 m) and evaluating population trends of the B.
irregularis are analyzed in this paper to evaluate the effectiveness of these barriers. With the
1.2 m barrier, only snakes in the largest size class were able to climb over the barrier. Snake
collections had shown that all the large snakes were males, suggesting that if the smaller female
snakes can be excluded, reproduction and establishment of new breeding populations can be
inhibited. The 1.5 m barrier proved to be 100 percent effective in preventing snakes from all
size classes to climb over. The snake may never be eradicated on Guam, but through
management techniques such as the barrier testing done in this study, its disastrous effects
could be avoided on other islands.
