TI  - Riffles and Pools: Should Resource Managers Be Sampling from Both Habitat Types in Rapid Bioassessments?
PY  - 1998
PB  - University of California, Berkeley
UR  - https://www.ocf.berkeley.edu/~pkmendez/envsci/projects/1998final/ChewT_1998.pdf
U1  - ChewT_1998-page1.pdf
AB  - The goal of bioassessment is to determine the ecological integrity of a water body from sampling of the biota. Using past studies that compared the macroinvertebrate fauna of riffles and pools I intended to determine whether assessments of ecological health based on limited sampling (to riffles only) as suggested by the U.S. Environmental Protection Agency (Plafkin 1989) provides an accurate assessment of biological integrity. A survey of the literature on riffle pool comparisons was done to determine differences between riffle and pool fauna. Where species lists are provided, I computed the following bioassessment indices: family richness, Family Biotic Index (FBI), and %EPT for riffle-only, pool-only and a composite of riffle and pool data. The analysis performed indicates that richness increases with more habitats sampled. There was a significant difference between FBI and %EPT calculated from riffle samples versus pool samples. I conclude from my survey and subsequent analysis of data from past studies that riffle-only sampling causes loss of important information about water quality because riffle communities are distinct from pool communities and therefore is differently sensitive to water quality changes such as sedimentation.
