UR  - https://www.ocf.berkeley.edu/~pkmendez/envsci/projects/1998final/ChiuM_1998.pdf
U1  - ChiuM_1998-page1.pdf
AB  - This research project tested whether eucalyptus soil from a site at Oakwood Valley Park in Marin would inhibit the germination and growth of several native species. This would help predict whether future plantings of native Valley Live Oaks would survive in soil previously occupied by Eucalyptus globulus. Soil samples of oak and eucalyptus were taken from the site and the experiment was carried out on the UC Berkeley campus. I measured the germination rates of four different native species (Achillea millefonium, Festuca californica, Layia platyglossa, and Eschscholzia californica) in both eucalyptus and oak soil and compared results to determine whether a relationship exists between soil type and germination rate. In order to look at effects on growth, I also planted a native grass and a native forb, Festuca Californica and Layia Platyglossa, in both oak and eucalyptus soil. Data of number of leaves were gathered over a period of three weeks, along with total biomass and compared to see whether there is a notable difference in growth. Experiment data indicates no significant difference in the growth of the grass . between the two types of soil. In the germination tests, however, oak soil in genereal yields higher germination rates. Although it has been shown that eucalyptus may produce toxic compounds, this may not inhibit growth of other species. Therefore, replanting the site with native oaks may not be problematic.
