AU  - Andrea P. Clark
TI  - Water Laws in California and Ecuador
PY  - 1998
PB  - University of California, Berkeley
UR  - https://www.ocf.berkeley.edu/~pkmendez/envsci/projects/1998final/ClarkAP_1998.pdf
U1  - ClarkAP_1998-page1.pdf
AB  - Significantly greater environmental degradation is occurring in underdeveloped nations than in developed nations today.  An example is water pollution in Ecuador, where water laws are similar to California's, but the results are dramatically different.  A major reason for this difference is that the political conditions surrounding the formation of the two regions' water laws were vastly different.  In California, water protection was recognized as a necessary measure to prevent water scarcity, a threat posed by a rapidly growing population in the 1950s.  In Ecuador, water protection was the result of a political power struggle in which a nationalist military government gained control of the resource.  California's relative success in water policy enforcement can be traced to this divergence in water protection motives between California and Ecuador.
