AU  - Birgit Claus
TI  - The Role of Riparian Vegetation in Intercepting Nitrate
PY  - 1998
PB  - University of California, Berkeley
UR  - https://www.ocf.berkeley.edu/~pkmendez/envsci/projects/1998final/ClausB_1998.pdf
U1  - ClausB_1998-page1.pdf
AB  - Nitrate in runoff from upland areas toward streams can be intercepted by vegetation in riparian zones, but the variability in uptake between species is poorly understood. I studied the effectiveness of various species in nitrate uptake in a simulated riparian zone, using a controlled greenhouse mesocosm experiment. Known concentrations of nitrate were applied to riparian channels which contained plants of approximately equal age in coarsely-grained sand of low organic content. Nitrate was extracted using KCl to measure nitrate uptake amounts over time for Populus (cottonwood), Alnus (alder), Salix (willow), and Arundo (giant reed) spp. Root mass and length were measured to standardize nitrate uptake levels for variations in plant size. I expected interception to be highest in channels containing all four species. This would indicate that maintenance of biologically diverse riparian zones is essential to the removal of excess nitrate from surface runoff and groundwater. I examined invasive giant reed for the potential threat it poses to native vegetation by conducting physiological tests, including stomatal conductance and water potential. I expected nitrate uptake levels of giant reed to be comparable to those of native species, thereby reducing excess nitrate flow into water. Related research, however, suggests that giant reed threatens biodiversity of riparian ecosystems. (Since this is an ongoing project, the full paper will appear in the 1999 Environmental Science 196 volume.)
