AU  - Julianne Emoto
TI  - Catalytic Chemical Oxidation of Hazardous Waste
PY  - 1998
PB  - University of California, Berkeley
UR  - https://www.ocf.berkeley.edu/~pkmendez/envsci/projects/1998final/EmotoJ_1998.pdf
U1  - EmotoJ_1998-page1.pdf
AB  - As industry and technology have increased, so has the generation of various hazardous wastes. Studies of various treatment alternatives have become increasingly necessary in order to deal with the accumulation of hazardous waste. Catalytic chemical oxidation, an example of a thermal treatment, was examined by this study. Past studies of oxidation processes have focused on individual chemicals at smaller quantities and higher temperatures. Although these past studies have been done, not much is known about when various chemicals are combined and when water content of wastewater is increased in order to use steam as a mechanism for raising oxidation temperatures. Therefore this study focused on the mixture and steam effect of the treatment of the catalytic chemical oxidation system. Results showed complete oxidation of observed mixtures of chemicals. This indicated the oxidation system is an efficient method of treating various hazardous wastes. In addition, raising water content lead to steam, which raised oxidation temperatures therefore increasing the efficiency of the system. However, in this study, limitations of raising water content were also observed, as water can also serve to quench the oxidation system.
