AB  - Genista monspessulana, a woody perennial leguminous species native to the Mediterranean region of Europe, has become widely distributed throughout California. This species, along with others similar to it, has the potential to become a serious environmental probem. Genista monspessulana, is capable of invading areas of disturbance, because of its spread and promotion of germination, by management activities such as road maintenence, roadside slashing and burning. Genista monspessulana exhibits many properties which make it a good invader, the most important is its prolific seed production. Areas infested with French Broom stands have seed densities up to 10,000 seeds/m2. This non-native species threatens native biodiversity and is a possible fire hazard. Control methods currently used are aimed at removing the existing plant biomass by manual and mechanical means. G. monspessulana is thriving on Mt. Tamalpais because there are no natural enemies to control it, and there is a lot of disturbance. The prescribed burns of French Broom are the best management techniques used today. It is beneficial in exhausting the seed bank and preserving the ecosystem biodiversity. The use of techniques aimed at increasing the germination rates are the goal of my research. Is there a management technique which uses prescribed burns to induce germination, therefore exhausting the seedbank. What affects will fertilization and broadcast watering have on germination rates?
