AU  - Megan Fifer
TI  - The Role of Micronutrients in Bladder Cancer Remission: Vitamin A, C, E, and Folate
PY  - 1998
PB  - University of California, Berkeley
UR  - https://www.ocf.berkeley.edu/~pkmendez/envsci/projects/1998final/FiferM_1998.pdf
U1  - FiferM_1998-page1.pdf
AB  - How does the food we ingest affect health? What role does nutrition play in health maintenance? Do micronutrients really combat disease or prevent cancer? By studying the biochemistry of vitamins A, C, E, and folate and by reviewing previous nutrition studies, I have addressed these questions as they relate to the onset and duration of bladder cancer remission. With this knowledge I have proposed a therapeutic intervention trial (n=600; 300 men and 300 women); I propose to measure dietary intake of foods rich in the named micronutrients using an interview administered food frequency questionnaire and then supplement individuals with varying concentrations of oral micronutrients. Supplementation will vary depending upon the group in which the individual is randomized. My single-blinded study investigates the effects of megadose supplementation (n=100 men and 100 women), RDA supplementation (n=100 men and 100 women), and no supplementation (n=100 men and 100 women). All eligible individuals are diagnosed with stage II bladder cancer, are within the ages of 25 and 35, have normal glucose metabolism, are free of other diseases, and do not take hormonal replacements. Based on my background research, I expect the highest rate of and longest remission to be a result of megadose supplementation, followed by the RDA supplementation and lastly by no supplementation. Additionally, I expect the greatest rate of remission to be at the onset of the study, tapering off as time passes within the ten year period. Practices of nutritional balance have been documented by previously conducted studies to provide health benefits in terms of the prevention and treatment of disease. The degree of benefit varies between men and women, therefore my study population is divided by sex. With this background and with the results of my intervention clinical trial as evidence, I would like to propose the use of micronutrients in conjunction with conventional medicine to treat diseases such as cancer.
