UR  - https://www.ocf.berkeley.edu/~pkmendez/envsci/projects/1998final/FongJ_1998.pdf
U1  - FongJ_1998-page1.pdf
AB  - This study is an examination of the effectiveness of World Bank environmental policy in regulating environmental impacts of development projects in the People's Republic of China. An in-depth case study of China's second largest dam under construction, the Xiaolongdi Multipurpose Dam Project along the Yellow River, is presented. A brief environmental evaluation of the project is conducted as well as a comparison of concerns shared with the Three Gorges Dam Project. Three main questions are to be answered: 1) Are environmental policies of the World Bank in China adhered to? 2) Are such policies effective in abating environmental degradation in development projects? and 3) How do the internal operations of the World Bank in China impact the effectiveness of environmental projects? Conclusions drawn from this research show that violations of World Bank environmental policy are apparent in examining the Xiaolongdi Multipurpose Dam Project, environmental regulation by the World Bank is ineffective in preventing environmental degradation, and the lack of effectiveness in environmental regulation can be partially traced to problematic systems of accountability and economic priorities practiced by the World Bank.
