AU  - Gregory Frankel
TI  - Preliminary Studies Examining the Potential of Pseudomonas fluorescens as a Biological Fertilizer or Control Agent: Inoculation and Application
PY  - 1998
PB  - University of California, Berkeley
UR  - https://www.ocf.berkeley.edu/~pkmendez/envsci/projects/1998final/FrankelG_1998.pdf
U1  - FrankelG_1998-page1.pdf
AB  - In this study I examined the potential of Pseudomonas fluorescens as a large-scale organic fertilizer and/or biological control agent. Three questions, in particular, were asked: 1) How long does the bacteria persist in the soil following inoculation? 2) Does soil moisture content affect its survivorship? 3) If the bacteria is to be used by farmers through conventional irrigation systems, can P. fluorescens survive in tap water long enough for soil inoculation to be effective? P. fluorescens strain A506 (streptomycin and rifampicin resistant) was grown in Luria Broth. The exponential growth phase of the bacteria in the liquid medium ended with a final density of P. fluorescens between 3.7 x 10⁹ cfu/ ml and 1.2 x 10¹⁰ cfu/ ml. P. fluorescens was than inoculated into a non-sterile 50% clay-loam 50% sand soil, at a density of 6.0 x 10⁶ cfu/ g soil(dry) at 15% soil moisture and 25% soil moisture. Results of the experiment showed that the population of P. fluorescens began to decrease immediately following inoculation, and continued to decrease exponentially until extinction at approximately three weeks following inoculation. Soil moisture did not have a significant effect on survivorship. It is clear that the bacteria must be applied several times over a growing season in order for high populations to be maintained. Exactly how many times is unclear because the inoculated soils in this experiment were free of plant life which may have led to a more rapid decline in bacterial populations due to starvation. The survival of P. fluorescens when added to tap water following centrifugation from the growth media was analyzed at one hour and two hours. Results show that bacterial population density decreased by 54% during the centrifugation process, but actually increased 48% in between one hour and two hours. This demonstrates that P. fluorescens can survive in tap water long enough to be distributed through conventional irrigation systems on commercial farms. In conclusion, if further studies continue to demonstrate the benefits of P. fluorescens in agricultural systems, soil inoculation can be effective if it is done more than once per season.
