AB  - A comparative analysis of community participation in EPA- versus community-initiated brownfields redevelopment projects was conducted by researching three San Francisco Bay Area case studies, namely the EPA Brownfields Initiative pilot projects in Richmond and San Francisco and a project initiated by a community organization in San Francisco’s Mission District. Data was collected through interviews and document review. Using theoretical and practitioner frameworks for public participation, the mechanisms implemented to solicit participation were evaluated within the context of the redevelopment decisionmaking process. My findings reflect a need for improved resource allocation and exchange between government agencies and community groups in order to better coordinate the different types of participatory mechanisms employed by government and community groups. Such mechanism complementarity would maximize substantive participation by capitalizing on both community and government contributions in order to achieve a redevelopment project conceptualized and implemented in partnership with the affected constituency.
