TI  - Native Fish and Amphibian Introductions to Strawberry Creek
PY  - 1998
PB  - University of California, Berkeley
UR  - https://www.ocf.berkeley.edu/~pkmendez/envsci/projects/1998final/GoldL_1998.pdf
U1  - GoldL_1998-page1.pdf
AB  - Like many urban streams, Strawberry Creek experienced a major loss of native fish and amphibian species due to pollution, sedimentation, culverting, and other deleterious effects of human encroachment onto riparian areas. The purpose of this project was to ascertain the species of fish and amphibians that were historically found in the creek, and determine if these species could reestablish populations in Strawberry Creek in its present condition. Findings at prehistoric archaeological sites dating from 2500 years BP and historical fish census records dating from 1898 were analyzed in order to determine which species were native to Strawberry Creek. Habitat parameters of Strawberry Creek were also analyzed, including flow, depth, canopy cover, substrate, and vegetation to ascertain its present condition and capacity to provide suitable habitat to native species. Of the thirteen species of fish that were likely to be native to the creek, the most likely candidate for successful introduction was the prickly sculpin (Cottus asper). Several species of amphibians were also investigated, and the most likely to establish populations were the Pacific tree frog (Hyla regilla), the western toad (Bufo boreas), and the California newt (Taricha torosa). These four species are all found in other modified urban areas, which suggests they are suited to Strawberry Creek in its present condition. In March and May 1998, Pacific tree frogs and California newts were introduced as egg masses and larva to the creek. Monitoring of these populations is recommended to continue over the next ten years.
