AU  - Emily R. Goswami
TI  - EVALUATION OF VARIABLES USED IN NATIONAL TRITIUM LABELING FACILITY HEALTH RISK ASSESSMENT
PY  - 1998
PB  - University of California, Berkeley
UR  - https://www.ocf.berkeley.edu/~pkmendez/envsci/projects/1998final/GoswamiER_1998.pdf
U1  - GoswamiER_1998-page1.pdf
AB  - The National Tritium Labeling Facility (NTLF) continuously emits radioactive tritium into the surrounding environment. Local residents are very concerned about the possibility of development of cancer among the population from excessive radiation. The NTLF has conducted a health risk assessment based on population and individual risk. The assessment concludes that the risks associated with the tritium emissions are negligible. Since the public is skeptical about the validity of the methods used, I have conducted an assessment of the maximally exposed individual. The maximally exposed individual risk is associated with the combination of several factors which increase the risk. These factors include increased exposure to employees at the laboratory, increased concentration in the level of tritium in the air, decreased individual body weight, exposure to contaminated rainwater, exposure to an accident at the lab, and living near the lab. I discovered that using high, previously recorded, concentration of tritium made the largest difference in the relative risk. A large accidental release also made a significant difference in relative risk. However, the overall, absolute risks are so tiny that the changes in risks are negligible. It is highly unlikely that even the maximally exposed individual will develop cancer as a result of radiation from the NTLF.
