TI  - Conductivity, pH, and Turbidity as Effective Indicators of Urbanization and Water Monitoring Parameters
PY  - 1998
PB  - University of California, Berkeley
UR  - https://www.ocf.berkeley.edu/~pkmendez/envsci/projects/1998final/HoJ_1998.pdf
U1  - HoJ_1998-page1.pdf
AB  - Water quality of urban creeks is heavily dictated by the amount of pollutants entering into them. As a result, effective methods of monitoring the presence of pollutants, how urbanization influences these input, and a comprehensive determination of stream quality needs to be developed. This study investigated whether increasing levels of urbanization correlated with increasing conductivity, turbidity, and decreasing pH along Strawberry and Wildcat Creeks. Correlation between urbanization and the measured parameters was not found, possibly because the limited number of watersheds used gave data that only reflected local changes versus broad changes. Readings of pH were stable throughout both creeks. Conductivity and turbidity increased along Wildcat Creek, while along Strawberry Creek conductivity remained stable and turbidity increased along the upper stretch before decreasing. This study also evaluated whether the measurement of these parameters was an effective approach to indicating the overall quality of the creeks. It was determined that monitoring these parameters alone was insufficient in providing an overall picture of stream quality because of the effects of geological and local factors. It was also the conclusion that incorporating invertebrate study along with the tested parameters of this research can provide a more accurate picture of stream quality.
