TY  - THES
AU  - Judith Kim
TI  - CO2 Sequestration Using Wastewater Microalgae Cultivation using the Advanced Integrated Wastewater Pond System
PY  - 1998
PB  - University of California, Berkeley
UR  - https://www.ocf.berkeley.edu/~pkmendez/envsci/projects/1998final/KimJ_1998.pdf
U1  - KimJ_1998-page1.pdf
AB  - Accumulation of carbon dioxide in the atmosphere as a result of fossil fuel combustion has been linked to potential global climate change. Contrasted with the potential for negative environmental effects is the value of carbon dioxide as a resource for plant growth. Capture and use of the carbon dioxide by microalgae in wastewater reclamation systems has emerged as a promising technology to help reduce emissions from fossil fuel-fired power plants. I studied the controls of carbon sequestration by microalgae in a pond system at the Advanced Integrated Wastewater Pond System (AIWPS) at the Richmond Field Station. I used the Redfield ratio (C:N:P = 106:16:1) to compare the relative ratio of these elements in algae grown in the High Rate Pond (HRP). Over an 8 month period, the ratio of total nitrogen and soluble reactive phosphorus at the influent and the effluent of the HRP were 27.4 (8.3) and 30.2 (14.8), respectively. Based on these data, I hypothesized carbon limited algal production. To test the hypothesis, I performed weekly laboratory bench-scale experiments from September to December, 1997. The principle HRP algal species identified were Scendesmus, Chlorella, and Pediastrum. Addition of carbon dioxide at 22 ml/min approximately doubled the algal productivity as indicated by measurement of total suspended solids. My experiment showed that HRP of the AIWPS is carbon limited. My results suggest that there is a potential for mitigating industrial gaseous effluent that contains CO2 and feeding it into HRP to yield higher biomass.
