TI  - Transmission of Cultural Memory of Medicinal Foods in Chinese Community in Urban California
PY  - 1998
PB  - University of California, Berkeley
UR  - https://www.ocf.berkeley.edu/~pkmendez/envsci/projects/1998final/LaiAWC_1998.pdf
U1  - LaiAWC_1998-page1.pdf
AB  - Food remedy was traditionally believed to be the first line of defense when Chinese confronted minor health problems. Such health practice had been very popular because these foods not only relieve patient’s sickness, but can also provide physical comfort. As Chinese migration had increased in the US in past decades, people’s health beliefs had been changed along with their new lifestyles. This project was designed to investigate the pattern of change of such beliefs within and across different age groups and to describe observed patterns. This study targeted three age groups: youth (ages 15-25), middle-aged (ages 35-56), and elderly (ages 60-85). Each group was asked about their knowledge of and past experiences with food remedy by either interview (elderly and middle-aged) or questionnaire (youth). The study focused on three areas of interest: 1) the belief and use of food remedy among Chinese Americans evaluated, 2) their acquisition of knowledge of food remedy and 3) the role of the elderly and middle-aged groups in transmission of such knowledge. The results showed that the middle-aged and the elderly had the most comparable health beliefs and food habits than any other combinations of age groups. The reason was that elderly preserved and treasured more of cultural beliefs than any other age groups, and were more willing to pass the knowledge on to the next generation. Therefore the gap between elderly and middle-aged was smaller than that between the middle-age and youth. The youth, however, might be more susceptible to change and were easily influenced by the outside culture because of their ages; therefore the knowledge that they actually obtained from family might be limited.
