AU  - Clarence Kaizen Lee
TI  - Affects of Organic Loading Rates on Biogas Yields from Anaerobic Digestion
PY  - 1998
PB  - University of California, Berkeley
UR  - https://www.ocf.berkeley.edu/~pkmendez/envsci/projects/1998final/LeeCK_1998.pdf
U1  - LeeCK_1998-page1.pdf
AB  - The Advanced Integrated Wastewater Pond System (AIWPS) is a low technology wastewater treatment system which, along with the characteristic energetics, is ideal for use by undeveloped communities. A characteristic which defines the AIWPS is the emission of methane gas which is produced from anaerobic digestion of organic wastes, the first stage of sewage treatment. As opposed to aerobic degradation of waste, the conventional mechanism of wastewater treatment, which requires energy, the produced methane gas from the anaerobic digestion stage is a source of energy. The purpose of this stage is to maximize the rate of organic waste degradation and simultaneous methane production while minimizing the rate of untreated waste flowing to the next stage. Higher loading rates of wastewater increases the available organics for degradation, but it decreases the residence time of the organic wastes in the digestion tank. Therefore, as total biogas (i.e. methane, carbon dioxide, etc.) production rate increases, the efficiency of waste degradation decreases which decreases the yield of biogas per unit organic waste. When varying organic loading rates were compared to the resulting yields of biogas in two trial digester tanks, the yields of biogas decreased as the organic loading rate increased. In Digester 1(Small), the linear relationship was -1/∖gas yield = -1.3177 - 1.8977∖BOD. In Digester 2(Large), the linear relationship was -1/∖gas yield = -1.6319 - 2.6421 log BOD. Therefore, in treating higher rates of wastewater, the more organic wastes in effluent from anaerobic stage of the AIWPS remain untreated.
