PY  - 1998
PB  - University of California, Berkeley
UR  - https://www.ocf.berkeley.edu/~pkmendez/envsci/projects/1998final/LeeS_1998.pdf
U1  - LeeS_1998-page1.pdf
AB  - Pollution and contamination of our environment are great concerns to people and to organisms that depend on a clean habitat to survive. Bioremediation is a new attempt to treat pollution, whether the pollution is in the water or in the ground. Based on the 1994 Toxic Inventory Release database, produced by EPA, approximately 2.6 billion pounds of methyl ethyl ketone (MEK) and 78 million pounds of methyl isobutyl ketone (MIBK) were released over the years of 1992-1994 (EPA 1994a). It is important to understand how a chemical degrades. This research focused on the bioremediation of MIBK since work has been done on MEK. The first batch of MIBK degrading culture was derived from MEK degrading culture. By measuring the rate of oxygen uptake when microorganisms are consuming a carbon source, the oxidation rate was found. Respirometry was used to determine the oxidation rate of MIBK. The MIBK degrading culture followed the characteristics of the Michaelis-Menten equation. The Michaelis-Menten equation is V=(Vmax*S)/ Km + S where V is the rate of reaction, Vmax is the maximum reaction rate, S is the substrate concentration and Km is the half-saturation constant. Based on the curve obtained from respirometry analysis, the Vmax is 25.6 micromoles/Liter per minute per biomass while the Km is 12 micromoles/Liter MIBK. Even though the Vmax and Km has been determined, more work is needed to confirm results.
