PY  - 1998
PB  - University of California, Berkeley
UR  - https://www.ocf.berkeley.edu/~pkmendez/envsci/projects/1998final/LevyR_1998.pdf
U1  - LevyR_1998-page1.pdf
AB  - The effect of leaf leachates on the survival, growth and activity of Pacific tree frog (Hyla regilla) tadpoles was examined in a controlled laboratory setting. Leachates were prepared from fresh leaves of southern blue gum (Eucalyptus globulus), California bay (Umbellularia californica), coast redwood (Sequoia sempervirens) and coast live oak (Quercus agrifolia). Tadpoles were exposed to various concentrations of E. globulus leachate for a 10 day period and a mortality threshold for leachate concentration was found at the 1.9% leachate level. Mortality increased significantly in proportion to leachate concentration. Exposure to E. globulus leachate significantly reduced tadpole growth at a leachate concentration of 3.8%. All leachates caused similar levels of mortality and significantly decreased tadpole activity. Results indicate that leaf leachate can adversely impact water quality for tadpoles, as it contains high levels of phenolic compounds which may be directly toxic or induce hypoxia. Further research should be directed toward field studies to determine if polyphenol levels in nature can reach levels high enough to impact tadpoles and other freshwater organisms.
