TI  - Bike-to-Shuttle Intermodal Transportation as a Means of Commute
PY  - 1998
PB  - University of California, Berkeley
UR  - https://www.ocf.berkeley.edu/~pkmendez/envsci/projects/1998final/LewR_1998.pdf
U1  - LewR_1998-page1.pdf
AB  - Transportation choices have a significant impact on air quality. Motor vehicle trips of short duration have a proportionally higher emission rate of pollutants. By getting individuals out of single occupancy vehicles and onto bicycles and shuttles for short commute trips, a reduction in pollution emissions can be realized. Bike-to-shuttle intermodal transportation is one solution for replacing single occupancy vehicles on our roadways. Through my research, I sought to determine what constitutes a successful bike-to-shuttle intermodal transportation project, and how such a project can be best adapted for the Lawrence Berkeley National Laboratory in order to accommodate its employees' specific needs. To do this, I conducted a survey of Berkeley Lab employees to determine their specific transportation decisions and concerns. In addition, I evaluated other bicycle intermodal transportation projects to discover what constitutes a successful project. The results show that implementing an improved bicycle intermodal project for Berkeley Lab employees may be a challenge because of specific conditions such as distance and geography associated with the Lab. In addition, employees are satisfied with their current transportation choices (77% of those surveyed are single occupancy drivers) and are predominantly unwilling to forgo their current convenient mode of transportation for a mode that may require more time and inconvenience. For the Berkeley Laboratory to attract and retain bicycle commuters, disincentives for driving need to be coupled with incentives for bicycling and shuttling.
