TI  - Supermarket Composting: Policy and Implementation
PY  - 1998
PB  - University of California, Berkeley
UR  - https://www.ocf.berkeley.edu/~pkmendez/envsci/projects/1998final/LiewL_1998.pdf
U1  - LiewL_1998-page1.pdf
AB  - My research focused on how supermarkets can contribute to reducing solid waste in order to help individual cities attain the 50 percent source reduction goal by the year 2000. More specifically, I looked at current disposal practices of food waste by supermarkets to see if they have considered composting as a viable option. I conducted three case studies: Vons (currently composts its food waste), Safeway (recently began a composting program that mirrors Vons), and Lucky (disposes of its food waste). I obtained data through telephone and personal interviews of different personnel from these companies. I asked them a set of questions in order to understand what caused or impeded the company from adopting a composting program. The interviews and case studies show that these companies primarily began a composting program when a composting facility brings the idea to the company and works with the supermarket to efficiently implement the program. A secondary way of starting a program is to simply follow the pattern of the innovator and copy their methods. For supermarkets that do not compost, the two main hindrances are lack of information and lack of a composting facility that is willing to initiate the process of making the policy.
