TI  - The Potential Distribution and Abundance of Zebra Mussels in California
PY  - 1998
PB  - University of California, Berkeley
UR  - https://www.ocf.berkeley.edu/~pkmendez/envsci/projects/1998final/MehtaS_1998.pdf
U1  - MehtaS_1998-page1.pdf
AB  - Since its initial introduction to North America in the 1980s, the zebra mussel (Dreissena polymorpha) has rapidly established in many water bodies east of the Continental Divide, altering native aquatic communities and causing economic damage. To assess the potential for the zebra mussel to invade California, I examined the suitability of water bodies in California to support it. I researched zebra mussel tolerance thresholds for various water quality variables, such as turbidity and discharge, and compared them with California water quality data from governmental agencies to determine locations suitable for colonization and population growth. I then estimated boat traffic at these regions, as boats are the predominant vector for introduction. I found that several water bodies in California, particularly aqueducts, reservoirs, and canals, have suitable habitat characteristics for zebra mussels. My analysis indicates that preventative measures, such as thorough inspections of boats, should be taken to impede introduction of zebra mussels and a plan should be prepared to mitigate impacts and prevent spread should they arrive.
