PY  - 1998
PB  - University of California, Berkeley
UR  - https://www.ocf.berkeley.edu/~pkmendez/envsci/projects/1998final/MonasterskyN_1998.pdf
U1  - MonasterskyN_1998-page1.pdf
AB  - One of the greatest environmental threats to health in the developing countries of Asia is indoor air pollution. Exposure to indoor air pollution is largely attributed to significant amounts of coal used for cooking and heating in homes. Women, in charge of household chores and cooking, are particularly exposed to magnified levels of coal smoke and have elevated indices of lung cancer. In order to reduce the risk of lung cancer, the local residents must be made aware of the risks associated with the current use of coal for cooking and heating. A number of programs, such as the Chinese National Improved Stove Program, have been promoting the use of improved cookstoves. The effectiveness of disseminating improved cookstoves is measured by how many people are using the new stoves. Individuals are prone to switch to new stoves when variables including cost of product, efficiency, and relative value are deemed worthwhile in terms of reducing threats to health and the environment. Education about long term health risks is vital to the welfare of the Chinese people; the subsequent implementation of improved cookstoves increases when people are educated about their options and about the consequences.
