TI  - Title Transfer Compliance Evaluation of Berkeley's Commercial Energy Conservation Ordinance (Ordinance 6176-N.S.)
PY  - 1998
PB  - University of California, Berkeley
UR  - https://www.ocf.berkeley.edu/~pkmendez/envsci/projects/1998final/NaugleDP_1998.pdf
U1  - NaugleDP_1998-page1.pdf
AB  - The city of Berkeley in California has adopted the Commercial Energy Conservation Ordinance (CECO), which requires that commercial businesses install energy efficient measures at the time of sale or renovation to meet a minimum energy efficiency level. This study was designed to evaluate CECO compliance with regard to title transfers. The Ordinance is still in its infancy which allowed the entire population to be examined. Title transfer and CECO permit data from January 1994 through December 1997 were analyzed to produce the base compliance ratios. During this period there were 291 title transfer of which 23 % triggered CECO. Compliance for the four year period was near constant, not fluctuating more then 3 % in any year. Levels of compliance for the purposes of this study are defined as: full compliance, partial compliance, or non-compliance. The data shows a full compliance level of 2 %, a partial compliance of 20 %, and a non-compliance of 78 %. The investigation identifies four major problems with CECO causing poor compliance: (1) There is no tracking system or enforcement process following up CECO applications requests. (2) Current CECO informational material and application forms are confusing, and generally unprofessional in their appearance. (3). Distribution of CECO information is inconsistent causing low awareness about the ordinance. (4) Lack of communication between the City, real estate agents and major title companies creates an apathetic sentiment in the realty and title company community and building owners leading to low participation.
