AU  - John T. Newberg
TI  - Ion Flotation: Predicting Metal Removal Rates From Surface Tension Measurements
PY  - 1998
PB  - University of California, Berkeley
UR  - https://www.ocf.berkeley.edu/~pkmendez/envsci/projects/1998final/NewbergJT_1998.pdf
U1  - NewbergJT_1998-page1.pdf
AB  - In light of strict regulations imposed by the government on the discharge of industrial effluents into our surface waters, chemical and metallurgical industries are continually seeking new technologies to efficiently remove metals from dilute aqueous systems. Ion flotation is a process involving the foam separation of metal ions from dilute metal-contaminated solutions that has the potential of treating large amounts of effluent while achieving very low final metal concentrations. Metal adsorption density estimates are central to the understanding of ion flotation as a thermodynamic process. In this investigation, surface tension measurements of solutions containing dodecylsulfate and tetradecylsulfate were studied as a function of the concentration of these surfactants. A semi-empirical expression was then derived to predict the adsorption density of the metal ions at the solution-air interface using surface tension data. Metal removal rates estimated from these adsorption density calculations matched well with those of actual removal rates from ion flotation. These findings suggest that ion flotation may be driven by fundamental thermodynamics. This provides a basis for industries to further exploit the use of various surfactants and utilize surface tension measurements as a means for predicting the thermodynamic behavior of these surfactants towards the removal of specific metal ions via ion flotation.
