AB  - The Vietnamese government’s recent attempts at structural and institutional reform have resulted in radical changes economically and agriculturally. Economic liberalization has introduced free market forces into agricultural production, trade, and management. A series of accelerated infrastructural and technological investments have been made to further the goal of maximizing agricultural output; especially of rice. This paper is a study of Vietnam’s macroeconomic and agricultural reforms and how they have affected rice production in the Mekong River Delta over recent decades. Although rice production averages have risen steadily over the past decade, the effects of agricultural reform have not been uniform throughout the country. Certain provinces within the Mekong River Delta have experienced different rates of change of rice production, rice yield, and area sown.
