AU  - Christine Quan
TI  - The Effect of Window Position on Indoor Residential Environmental Tobacco Smoke
PY  - 1998
PB  - University of California, Berkeley
UR  - https://www.ocf.berkeley.edu/~pkmendez/envsci/projects/1998final/QuanC_1998.pdf
U1  - QuanC_1998-page1.pdf
AB  - The adverse health effects associated with Environmental Tobacco Smoke (ETS) have been widely reported in many studies. Since most human activity occurs in the home environment, assessing indoor residential ETS exposure is needed. Few field studies have measured the role of ventilation on ETS contaminant levels in a real world environment. In the current pilot study, we investigated the extent to which open windows as compared to closed windows reduced ETS contaminant levels of respirable suspended particles (RSP), polycyclic aromatic hydrocarbons (PAHs), and nicotine in a closed indoor home environment. We found that opening windows did not make a consistent difference in reducing RSP and PAH levels but did result in increasing fluctuations in these contaminant concentrations across experiments. Inadequate ventilation and air mixture in the room could be associated with these fluctuations. Most RSP and PAH levels varied by a factor of two in each experiment. Weather conditions and smoking style could be two factors why RSP and PAH levels differed between trials. No correlation was found between RSP and PAH levels. In addition, no conclusions about nicotine levels could be made from this study. Future field studies investigating the role of ventilation in reducing residential ETS pollutants need to better monitor and control physical parameters. Air mixing should be monitored with an instrument or a tracer gas that can directly measure ventilation rate. Weather conditions inside and outside of the room should be closely monitored. Moreover, parameters such as cross ventilation and smoking style can be better controlled with proper choice of windows to open and a smoking machine. This pilot study demonstrated the complexity of evaluating the effect of ventilation in decreasing ETS contaminants and will aid future studies in improving their methodology to measure residential tobacco smoke.
