TI  - Altenative Trade: Its Effectiveness in Helping Coffee Growers in Chiapas, Mexico
PY  - 1998
PB  - University of California, Berkeley
UR  - https://www.ocf.berkeley.edu/~pkmendez/envsci/projects/1998final/RangelM_1998.pdf
U1  - RangelM_1998-page1.pdf
AB  - Developing countries have historically been dependent on export cash crops as a source of currency, but often the communities producing these goods are not the ones benefiting from international trade. Small scale coffee producers in Mexico exemplify this. The recent evolution of the coffee trade has further marginalized these peasants. This is especially true for the peasants in the poorest state in Mexico, Chiapas, where most farmers own less than 5 hectares of land. To counter this, Alternative Trade Organizations (ATOs) formed networks to aid peasants in international trading. This study investigates the effects ATOs have had on marginalized communities. Most of the data was obtained through interviews and surveys conducted on peasants. ATOs help peasants through offering higher coffee prices and increasing yield through the use of organic fertilizer and renovation. ATOs also help establish health facilities, schools, and other development projects. Technicians help families learn about organic agriculture and ways to combat pests without the use of chemicals. There are, however, many restraints on the effectiveness of ATOs in helping marginalized communities. Many farmers are not trading through ATOs because they are either unaware of ATOs, lack the organization that trading through an ATO requires, or they lack the money technicians charge to certify. This leaves the most marginalized peasants without acess to ATOs and farmers who already have resources to benefit from alternative trade.
