TI  - Acquisition of Natural Lands by the Washington State Government by
PY  - 1998
PB  - University of California, Berkeley
UR  - https://www.ocf.berkeley.edu/~pkmendez/envsci/projects/1998final/SuttorpK_1998.pdf
U1  - SuttorpK_1998-page1.pdf
AB  - In this paper I consider the role of two elements of natural resource agency behavior--agency dependency on external support and professional expertise-- and assess their relevance to the behavior of agencies concerned with land acquisition in Washington State. In order to learn about land acquisition in general and in Washington State, in particular, I conducted interviews with several agency officials and other parties involved in the land acquisition process in order to determine how land acquisition programs operate. Since most of the agencies concerned with conservation of natural lands rely primarily on the Washington Wildlife and Recreation Program (WWRP) for their projects' funding, I discuss the manner by which the three primary land acquisition agencies-- State Parks and Recreation Commission, State Department of Natural Resources and State Department of Fish & Wildlife-- relate to the WWRP and analyze the roles that expertise and external support might play in mediating this relationship. Finally, I assess the process for acquiring land for two different purposes through the WWRP for habitat conservation and outdoor recreation. I explore which has been the most successful as a function of agency external support and expertise. In order to illustrate the dynamic state of the program, I briefly consider the implications for current salmon restoration programs on the program's funding structure.
