AB  - When the U.S. Environmental Protection Agency issued regulations in 1988 to curb the proliferation of leaking underground storage tanks, it gave affected parties a decade to comply. Now, just six months away from the December 1998 deadline, only half of all regulated tanks in the United States are in full compliance. Enforcement of UST regulations at the local agency level is becoming more significant as the deadline approaches. This research project will evaluate the level of California local agency enforcement of the December 1998 UST deadline for upgrading and replacing tanks and identify certain characteristics which promote or hinder an agency's success. Correlation analysis will demonstrate that external factors, such as economic resources and social structure of the regulated community, can not be individually correlated. Instead, a more tangible correlation with agency performance can be found at the organizational and bureaucratic level. Senate Bill 1082 (SB 1082) set up Certified United Program Agencies (CUPAs) which were intended to coordinate local agency efforts. Attempts to coordinate agency efforts failed in certain counties, where the level of compliance to the December 1998 deadline is lowest.
