PB  - University of California, Berkeley
UR  - https://www.ocf.berkeley.edu/~pkmendez/envsci/projects/1998final/WangA_1998.pdf
U1  - WangA_1998-page1.pdf
AB  - Streams and rivers are becoming increasingly contaminated with nutrients due to agricultural practices. Most noticeably, there have been huge increases in the amount of nitrogen fertilizers used, which in turn release nitrates into the ground and surface water through leaching and runoff. The focus of this study will be to see if there is any correlation between Arundo donax density and nitrate concentrations in the groundwater of California’s major streams and rivers. Nitrate data was collected through the Environmental Protection Agency’s STORET system and will be limited to the past three decades. Arundo donax distribution throughout California was obtained through collaborations with Tom Dudley and Jim Robins at the University of California at Berkeley, as well as through various agencies throughout California. Nitrates potentially promote the growth of Arundo donax in California, an invasive plant species. Arundo donax is present in over half of California’s major streams and rivers. It displaces native riparian vegetation and destroys the habitats of native wildlife. This study has shown that nitrate levels of 0.06 mg/l or greater tend to be associated with Arundo donax growth since the streams and rivers that had Arundo in them almost all had nitrate levels this high. Therefore, fertilizer use needs to be decreased so that we can preserve our water quality as well as protect the biodiversity of our ecosystem.
