AU  - Sarah Willan Weekes
TI  - The Effects of Air Pollution on San Francisco Architecture
PY  - 1998
PB  - University of California, Berkeley
UR  - https://www.ocf.berkeley.edu/~pkmendez/envsci/projects/1998final/WeekesSW_1998.pdf
U1  - WeekesSW_1998-page1.pdf
AB  - The goal of this study was to determine whether air pollution negatively affects San Francisco architecture. To test this question, a general survey of the ways that different air pollutants react with different materials was completed. After the application of this information to the Bay Area, a visual survey of San Francisco buildings was completed. The selection of three buildings, the Palace of Fine Arts, San Francisco City Hall, and the Palace of the Legion of Honor was accomplished using archival review, information obtained by personal interviews, and a more substantial survey of San Francisco buildings. These structures were used to test the study's hypothesis that air pollution does cause damage to architecture in San Francisco. Results did support the hypothesis; damage, such as erosion and black soot deposits upon stonework and corrosion of metals, was evident. Due to the types of damage and prevalence of certain air pollutants in the Bay Area, it was deduced that Particulate Matter (PM) and ozone are to blame for the damage.
