TY  - THES
AU  - Henry Wong
TI  - Trichloroethylene Plumes in Southwest Berkeley
PY  - 1998
PB  - University of California, Berkeley
UR  - https://www.ocf.berkeley.edu/~pkmendez/envsci/projects/1998final/WongH_1998.pdf
U1  - WongH_1998-page1.pdf
AB  - Zoned for manufacturing purposes by Berkeley’s Planning Commission, Southwest Berkeley’s potential for trichloroethylene (TCE) plumes is high due to the prevalent usage of TCE-containing chemicals. With sparse data from different regulatory reports, undetected TCE plumes may exist beneath private and corporate properties. This project is intended to provide a clearer picture of whether TCE plumes are present in the area bounded by San Pablo Avenue (east), Aquatic Park (west), Carleton Street (north), and Ashby Avenue (south). I reviewed active files of monitoring well reports to gather information on the presence and/or concentrations of trichloroethylene. Then, I charted the TCE concentrations on a map. From the map, I applied a simplified version of the Wedge Model to construct the plumes, neglecting source locations and flow rates (Fischer 1998, pers. comm.). A simplified Wedge Model provided a sufficient method to identify plumes because the sources are unknown and plumes existed for at least several years. Based on TCE concentrations from sites in the area, two potential plumes were identified. The first plume centered around an area occupied by the Emerald Packaging Company (Site A) and Proen Products Company (Site G). The other plume involved the National Starch and Chemical Company (Site D). Several constraints prevented me from creating a more detailed picture of the area. First, the Berkeley Toxics Management Department did not have enough files with sufficiently detailed information regarding TCE presence or absence over time. Supplementing existing files with additional soil samples required timely gauged laboratory analyses and additional funding. More plumes may have existed and the plumes that I described might be part of a single larger plume; insufficient data and an artificial boundary necessitated by time constraints limited the scope of this project. Future research should run analytical tests for each block to clarify whether the plumes in Southwest Berkeley are connected or extended beyond my boundaries.
