AU  - Frank T. Yoo
TI  - Elimination of Coliform Bacteria Using Advanced Integrated Wastewater Pond Systems
PY  - 1998
PB  - University of California, Berkeley
UR  - https://www.ocf.berkeley.edu/~pkmendez/envsci/projects/1998final/YooFT_1998.pdf
U1  - YooFT_1998-page1.pdf
AB  - Untreated or improperly treated wastewater effluent that is discharged into major waterways can lead to environmental problems of eutrophication, degradation in biotic diversity, and epidemic human health risks. Therefore, efficient reduction of source pollutants in the wastewater is an important step in preserving the health of natural waterways as well as the health of the organisms and people that use them. This experiment evaluates the effectiveness of the Advanced Integrated Wastewater Pond System (AIWPS)--located at the University of California, Berkeley, Richmond Field Station--in removing pathogenic coliform bacteria from raw domestic sewage. The results of the study show that total coliform and more specifically, E. coli, densities (measured as Most Probable Number per 100mL of sample) decrease as the wastewater flows from one pond to the next in the series described by the AIWPS. It is also found that based on the stock density flows (of coliform and E. coli) and residence times of the four ponds studied in this experiment, each successive pond is more efficient at removing coliform bacteria than the previous pond in the series of four. Although the bacterial densities found in the final effluent of the AIWPS exceeded USEPA reuse water quality guidelines, these shortcomings may have been influenced by experimental biases in the data, and an inappropriate experimental approach. Nevertheless, past data records and other studies confirm that this cost effective, resourceful, efficient, and reliable wastewater treatment system is extremely valuable in its potential for providing resources like reusable quality water, fuel, and fertilizer.
