AU  - Neil D. Ahlsten
TI  - The Recovery of Ceanothus gloriosus var. porrechtus following the 1995 Point Reyes fire
PY  - 1997
PB  - University of California, Berkeley
UR  - https://www.ocf.berkeley.edu/~pkmendez/envsci/projects/1997final/AhlstenND_1997.pdf
U1  - AhlstenND_1997-page1.pdf
AB  - In this study I analyze the post fire recovery of two populations of the endangered species Ceanothus gloriosus var. porrechtus during its second year of recovery. Decades of fire suppression at Point Reyes National Seashore have prevented the regeneration of ceanothus stands in an area of California chaparral prone to frequent natural fires. To analyze potential competition during seedling establishment, I compared seedling densities with the density of other plant species. Results show no evidence for interspecific competition in seedling recruitment through May of 1997. I also compared the amount of seedling recruitment in burned and unburned populations for the two years following the fire. While burned areas had very high levels of seedling recruitment, unburned areas had none. This shows the dependency which C. gloriosus has upon fire and illustrates the importance of incorporating this requirement for periodic fire into the Point Reyes fire management plan.
