AU  - Janice Alexander
TI  - The Distribution of Spartina alterniflora in San Francisco Bay: A Study of Invasion and Restoration
PY  - 1997
PB  - University of California, Berkeley
UR  - https://www.ocf.berkeley.edu/~pkmendez/envsci/projects/1997final/AlexanderJ_1997.pdf
U1  - AlexanderJ_1997-page1.pdf
AB  - Spartina alterniflora is a non-indigenous cordgrass found in the tidal marshes of San Francisco Bay. Originally introduced in the early 1970's as part of tidal marsh restoration projects, the species has spread and invaded new sites, including marshes of previous restoration efforts. This study addresses the invasion of S. alterniflora by mapping its current distribution and comparing presence and absence on mudflats, natural marsh, and restored marsh, and potential invasion sites. Spartina alterniflora is currently found in a small number of mudflats and marshes but its spread seems relatively rapid compared to spread of other non-indigenous Spartina species present in the Bay. A higher percentage of restored marshes were invaded than natural marshes. The proximity of S. alterniflora to a new site is related to that site's invasion potential; restoration of diked baylands and salt ponds to contiguous tracts of tidal marsh increases the potential spread of this species. Spartina alterniflora invades completed restoration projects and threatens future restoration efforts in the San Francisco Bay.
