AB  - The endangered Mission Blue Butterfly (Plebejus icariodes missionensis) inhabits Milagra Ridge and is a member of the Lycaenidae, which are known to form symbiotic relationships with various ant species. P. i. missionensis larvae have been observed in myrmecophilous relationships with Prenolepis imparis, but interactions with other ant species remain undocumented. Research indicates that nonindigenous ant species, such as the Argentine ant (Iridomyrmex humilis), may pose a threat to the Mission Blue Butterfly larvae. Consequently, arthropod assemblages were censused at Milagra Ridge to characterize the insect fauna and its interaction with the Mission Blue Butterfly larvae. Pitfall traps showed a low diversity of arthropods with no known exotic ant species. The research suggests that the low diversity may be due to the small size of the reserve where the butterfly is found.
