AU  - Andrew Q. Britton
TI  - Comparison of the Small Mammal Fauna of Quercus agrifolia and Umbellularia californica Woodlands and E. globulus Stands
PY  - 1997
PB  - University of California, Berkeley
UR  - https://www.ocf.berkeley.edu/~pkmendez/envsci/projects/1997final/BrittonAQ_1997.pdf
U1  - BrittonAQ_1997-page1.pdf
AB  - Differences in the density and diversity of mammal species were investigated on plots in two forest stands, Quercus agrifolia (coast live oak) and Umbellularia californica (California bay) stands and Eucalyptus globulus (blue gum eucalyptus) stands. Five species were found during the course of the study which was conducted from March 19 through April 21. Peromyscus californicus(California mouse) and Neotoma fuscipes (Dusky-footed wood rat) were only found on the oak / bay sites whereas Mus musculus (house mouse) was only found in Eucalyptus sites. P. maniculatus (deer mouse) was found on both sites but only two individuals were found in Eucalyptus. P.truei (pinyon mouse) was also found on both sites but populations were significantly greater in oak sites, accounting for 68% of captures. Selectivity of each mammal species was measured for a variety habitat characteristics. This measure was the percent difference for sites where each species was found at as compared to the average value of all sites sampled. P. californicus was found to be the most selective. P . truei was found to be a generalist. Percent canopy and vegetation density was also greater on oak / bay sites and was an attribute that was selected for by all species except M. musculus. Using the selectivity indices and an index of food availability, vegetative cover was determined to be the variable that was most likely responsible for the variations in mammal distributions.
