AU  - Meredith Cecil
TI  - Science Education: A Comparison of Active and Passive Teaching Approaches
PY  - 1997
PB  - University of California, Berkeley
UR  - https://www.ocf.berkeley.edu/~pkmendez/envsci/projects/1997final/CecilM_1997.pdf
U1  - CecilM_1997-page1.pdf
AB  - This study investigated two methods of teaching science in elementary schools: the active and passive teaching approaches. This study was initiated in order to determine whether one of the methods of teaching science increased students' retention and comprehension of lesson material more so than the other. My hypothesis is that the active method results in better retention and comprehension. Sixty-eight students from four Berkeley-area 3rd and 4th grade classrooms, were involved in the study. Pre-tests and identical post-tests were administered to all students and an index was created by determining the difference between the post-test and pre-test scores for each student. The means of the indices for both the passive and active methods were computed and analyzed by a one-tailed t-test. Results supported the hypothesis that active teaching did indeed help students retain and comprehend the lesson material significantly better than passive teaching.
