AU  - Brent R. Chalem
TI  - The Study of Tick Host Specificity Examining the Behavioral Patterns of Dermacentor occidentalis (Pacific Coast Tick) and Ixodes pacificus (Western Black-Legged Tick)
PY  - 1997
PB  - University of California, Berkeley
UR  - https://www.ocf.berkeley.edu/~pkmendez/envsci/projects/1997final/ChalemBR_1997.pdf
U1  - ChalemBR_1997-page1.pdf
AB  - Ticks transmit more infectious agents than any other arthropod
group. The collection of ticks is sometimes difficult and population
estimations can be somewhat rough. A standard lm2 cloth flag was used to
collect the two tick species. The problem with this method is that ticks can
easily drop-off the flag once they attach. In order to reduce tick drop-off,
two scented flags (human and dog) were challenged against the normal
unscented flag. The flags were tested both in the laboratory and in the field.
In the laboratory tests, the only significant difference in drop-off rate was
with the dog scented flag using the Ixodes pacificus species. The field
collections produced different results. In the high density areas, the
unscented flag's collection rate was not significantly different at the 95%
confidence level. The unscented/human comparison on the other hand was
significantly different at the 95% level. In low density areas, the unscented
flag was significantly different at the 95% level from the dog and human
scented flags. Hence, it is evident that a scented flag will increase tick
collection and slightly reduce drop-off rates.
