AU  - Cherilyn Chin
TI  - Stomatopods and Cryptofaunal Communities as Bioindicators of Eutrophication Stress on Coral Reefs
PY  - 1997
PB  - University of California, Berkeley
UR  - https://www.ocf.berkeley.edu/~pkmendez/envsci/projects/1997final/ChinC_1997.pdf
U1  - ChinC_1997-page1.pdf
AB  - Most of the world's population lives near coastlines, and the greatest population increases are expected to be in developing countries adjacent to tropical coral reefs. Simple and inexpensive community-based biological monitoring programs are needed for local peoples so they can determine how to protect this fragile and rapidly degrading resource. This study compares the use of the cryptofaunal coral reef community and stomtatopod crustaceans as bioindicators in tropical coral reef monitoring. The major port city of Ujung Pandang, Sulawesi, in Indonesia has a chronic source of pollution due to untreated sewage and agricultural run-off flowing directly onto its coral reefs. Inner sites near Ujung Pandang, mid-reef sites and offshore sites were sampled. A trend of higher species abundance and biomass in the inner sites was found for all organisms sampled except for the pollution-sensitive stomatopods and alpheid shrimp. Both community-level and single species monitoring have their advantages and disadvantages, and this study shows that community-level monitoring does not produce the statistically significant results that single species monitoring produces.
