AU  - Laura Cuoco
TI  - Light Level Effects on Nitrogen Removal by Algae in an Experimental Wastewater Pond System
PY  - 1997
PB  - University of California, Berkeley
UR  - https://www.ocf.berkeley.edu/~pkmendez/envsci/projects/1997final/CuocoL_1997.pdf
U1  - CuocoL_1997-page1.pdf
AB  - Treatment of wastewater in a pond system as opposed to a traditional, mechanical approach has been in use for approximately 25 years (Green et al. 1996). This alternative method originated from the need for re-usable wastewater in developing countries as traditional treatments require some resources that can not be found in these regions. When treating wastewater, one concern is over the removal of nitrogen (Green et al. 1996). However, in the Advanced Integrated Wastewater Pond System, algae are generated for a number of reasons including the uptake of nitrogen. This use of algae is beneficial in that the algae can be collected and re-used as a fertilizer with a high nutrient content. The ponds have been constructed in a unique manner to account for the amount of light needed to maintain enough algal growth. However, the effect of different light levels with respect to nitrogen uptake by algae has never been studied. Thus, the hypothesis I have tested is whether there would be any variance in this uptake if the ponds had been designed differently. To explore this question, I took samples from three points in the ponds and exposed them to two different light levels for a period of two weeks. In this time, I measured nitrogen, volatile suspended solids (VSS), pH and temperature. The results throughout the first week show a greater uptake of nitrogen in the samples in the lower light levels than in the higher light levels. Consistently higher temperatures and pH levels in the high light samples may have increased ammonia stripping and subsequently, lowered nitrogen uptake as nitrogen was lost to the atmosphere as ammonia gas. Over the last week, the samples from two of the points exhibited higher percentages in the high light level than in the lower light level while the reverse was true for the third point. Temperature readings were still high throughout this week but they were lower than at the end of the first week. pH levels dropped in the first two high level ponds while every other sample showed a steady increase in pH. It appears that lowering of the pH caused more nitrogen uptake in the first two samples and the higher pH levels of the other samples contributed to ammonia stripping and lower percentages of nitrogen removed by the algae.
