U1  - FoxworthyA_1997-page1.pdf
AB  - The United States water quality control program, guided by the Clean Water Act and the US Environmental Protection Agency, has been relatively unsuccessful at preventing Nonpoint Source water pollution. This paper discusses the actors involved in regulating water quality in the Stemple Creek Watershed in Marin County, California, a rural environment where nonpoint sources are the main threat to water. The paper analyzes how these actors work within established community social systems as a means of creating an interactive regulatory strategy. Using biological testing of water quality and social survey of ranchers within the watershed, the paper found that attempts at working within established community social structures is an effective and efficient water quality regulation strategy.
