AU  - Salima Hassanali
TI  - Do levels of PM10 below the current US standard pose a potential threat to health?
PY  - 1997
PB  - University of California, Berkeley
UR  - https://www.ocf.berkeley.edu/~pkmendez/envsci/projects/1997final/HassanaliS_1997.pdf
U1  - HassanaliS_1997-page1.pdf
AB  - This paper poses the predominant question of whether particulate matter (PM10) can potentially cause adverse health effects at levels below the current US EPA Standard of 150 ug/m3. Currently two distinct and dichotomous views exist on airborne particulates and their possible health risks to humans. The proponents believe that PM10 is casually linked with mortality and morbidity endpoints at levels below the present standard. As a result, this group advocates change of the status quo. However, the other competing side opposes any changes of the current standard because they believe that PM10 does not cause any dire medical risks. Therefore, in order to resolve this dilemma and to adequately answer the primary question of interest, I have implemented a Hypothesis Testing scheme in which five out of Hill's seven criteria for establishing "causality" are rigorously tested and evaluated. After researching the extensive evidence presented by the two competing sides, I have assessed in this thesis that three out of five criteria that were employed have effectively established causality between PM10 and various different health endpoints.
