AU  - Angelica M. Herrera
TI  - Invertebrate community reduction in response to Arundo donax invasion at Sonoma Creek
PY  - 1997
PB  - University of California, Berkeley
UR  - https://www.ocf.berkeley.edu/~pkmendez/envsci/projects/1997final/HerreraAM_1997.pdf
U1  - HerreraAM_1997-page1.pdf
AB  - The non-native grass, Arundo donax, invades riparian areas throughout California. It has been hypothesized that Arundo provides poorer quality habitat for native wildlife in riparian systems. In this study, I sampled invertebrates and other arthropods on Arundo, native willow vegetation (Salix sp.), and mixtures of the two vegetation types to determine how Arundo influences invertebrate composition at Sonoma Creek, Sonoma County, California. The total number of insects, total insect biomass and taxonomic richness of invertebrates associated with native vegetation was significantly higher than that associated with Arundo vegetation, while mixed vegetation supported intermediate levels of invertebrates. The species diversity index (H') associated with native vegetation stands was also higher than that of Arundo vegetation. Overall, I found that vegetation type is a significant factor reducing the abundance and diversity of invertebrates. Arundo invasion can potentially change the vegetation structure of riparian zones and in turn, jeopardize the survival of birds, and other wildlife, whose diets are largely composed of insects found in native vegetation.
