AU  - Andrea Jani
TI  - Parasitoid Interactions with the Codling Moth, Cydia pomonella
PY  - 1997
PB  - University of California, Berkeley
UR  - https://www.ocf.berkeley.edu/~pkmendez/envsci/projects/1997final/JaniA_1997.pdf
U1  - JaniA_1997-page1.pdf
AB  - Mastrus ridibundus (Hymenoptera: Ichneumonidae) and Liotryphon caudatus (Hymenoptera: Ichneumonidae) are known parasitoids of the codling moth, Cydia pomonella. While attempts are being made to use these parasitoids as biological control agents of the codling moth in orchards, little is known of their biology or behavior. This study examines the effects of interspecific competition on the number of codling moth larvae attacked and number of eggs laid by M. ridibundus and L. caudatus. Attack rates and numbers of eggs laid are being recorded for each parasitoid in two scenarios: phase I, in which Mastrus and Liotryphon are separated from each other, and phase II, in which Mastrus and Liotryphon are confined in single container. Results from phase I show higher overall attack rates for Liotryphon but more eggs laid during each attack by Mastrus. Liotryphon appears to avoid superparasitism while Mastrus does not. Attack rates for both parasitoid species appear to be density dependent. Phase II has not yet been implemented. Dibrachys cavus (Hymenoptera: Chalcidoidea) is known as a hyperparasitoid of the codling moth. This study examined whether it can act as a primary parasitoid as well. Dibrachys were repeatedly exposed to codling moth larvae but did not attack, suggesting that it acts solely as a hyperparasitoid in relation to the codling moth.
