AU  - Michael Kincaid
TI  - Complications of Exotic Plants in the Natural Vegetative Recovery of Eucalyptus globulus Eradication Sites
PY  - 1997
PB  - University of California, Berkeley
UR  - https://www.ocf.berkeley.edu/~pkmendez/envsci/projects/1997final/KincaidM_1997.pdf
U1  - KincaidM_1997-page1.pdf
AB  - This study documented the early stages of regeneration of native and exotic species to a cleared E. globulus area on Angel Island in the San Francisco Bay. The plants were monitored for abundance and percent cover to compare the rates of native and exotic species repopulation on the newly exposed soil, beginning shortly after eucalyptus removal in November 1996 and continuing until April 1997. In the absence of active vegetation management, exotic species and their abundance increased over the time period. Native species initially repopulated the sites more so than did exotic species, but subsequently declined as exotics increased. By April, exotics species outgained native species in percent cover and it appears native species were displaced by interspecific competition. From these initial observations, it is likely that a few exotic species will eventually expand over most of the site, reducing the probability of successful restoration of a native plant community. Alternatively, exotic species may only dominate until the soil recovers from physical disturbance whereupon native species may recover, but the influence of exotic species still retards this process. To foster regrowth of native vegetation, it may be necessary for resource managers to actively control the spread of exotic species.
