AB  - California currently employs a statewide fish monitoring system, known as the Toxic Substance Monitoring Program (TSMP), to ensure that contaminant concentrations off the coast do not reach unsafe levels. Polychlorinated biphenyls (PCBs), recognized as universal contaminants, are common in several species of edible fish. High levels of PCB contamination have been found in the white croaker (genyonemus lineatus), a popularly consumed species. Using data from the annual TSMP reports, my study will focus on: 1) the determination of significant levels of PCB concentrations in the white croaker, and 2) the comparison of PCB concentrations in white croaker from the San Francisco, Los Angeles, and San Diego regions.
