TI  - Reuse of Pond Effluents as Plant Fertilizer
PY  - 1997
PB  - University of California, Berkeley
UR  - https://www.ocf.berkeley.edu/~pkmendez/envsci/projects/1997final/KuAY_1997.pdf
U1  - KuAY_1997-page1.pdf
AB  - Waste stabilization ponds can provide reclaimed water for agricultural use and a potential fertilizer for crops. The goal of this research project was to determine the viability of using effluent from an Advanced Integrated Wastewater Pond System (AIWPS) as a suitable replacement for chemical fertilizers. Corn plants were grown from seed in low nutrient soil and treated with AIWPS effluent or a commercial fertilizer. Plants were monitored to determine the growth responses to each fertilizer treatment. It was found that corn treated with AIWPS effluent alone did not exhibit the same growth increases as those treated with the chemical fertilizer. Results from this experiment showed that plants treated with pond effluent alone does have greater height increase than water (P < 0.01). Plants treated with AIWPS effluent showed ca. 55% greater height increase than the control group. However, the chemical fertilizer group exhibited a height increase of 5.5 times of the AIWPS effluent. This lack of growth response from AIWPS effluent treated plants probably result from the relatively low nitrogen and phosphorus concentrations in the effluent. However, A possible way to make more effective use of the nutrients in the AIWPS effluent is to harvest algae from the ponds for soil amendment before seeding, then use the effluent to irrigate the plants to improve soil structure and fertility.
