AU  - Adam Patrick O'Connor
TI  - Competition as a Factor in S. foliosa and S. virginica Distribution
PY  - 1997
PB  - University of California, Berkeley
UR  - https://www.ocf.berkeley.edu/~pkmendez/envsci/projects/1997final/O'ConnorAP_1997.pdf
U1  - O'ConnorAP_1997-page1.pdf
AB  - Tidal salt marshes in San Francisco Bay are often dominated by two species of vegetation with a sharp ecotone defining the edges of their distributions. Spartina foliosa (Pacific cordgrass) is found at lower elevations while Salicornia virginica (Perennial pickleweed) is typically above the ecotone. This study is designed to determine the importance of interspecific competition as a factor limiting the ranges of these two species. Both species were transplanted across the ecotone into the zone dominated by the other species. Half of these transplants were planted into unmodified stands of the other species, while the other half was planted in an area in which the other species had been removed. The difference in survival rates for the two sets of transplants was used to determine the importance of competition as a limit on ranges. The results show that removing competition had a statistically significant effect on survival of Salicornia virginica but not on Spartina foliosa. I have concluded that competition does not seem to be a factor limiting of the range of S. foliosa, which is limited to areas of lower salinity. Competition, and possibly a physical factor like duration of tidal immersion, limit the seaward range of S. virginica is at this site.
