TI  - Analysis of Environmental Risk Financing Mechanisms
PY  - 1997
PB  - University of California, Berkeley
UR  - https://www.ocf.berkeley.edu/~pkmendez/envsci/projects/1997final/PhunADQ_1997.pdf
U1  - PhunADQ_1997-page1.pdf
AB  - Private sector attitudes toward environmental risk is a result of the day to day business operations of the firm. One of the main factors in determining the firm's operations is the cost of its production process. Environmental impact resulting from the firms' operations is an uncertain cost factor for the firm. Risk management by the firm is the process by which these uncertain factors are recorded as part of the firms' costs. Risk financing mechanisms are used to control the uncertain costs and reduce the possibility of business failure. Environmental risk financing mechanisms are financing mechanisms specifically used to control risks associated with environmental liability or remediation costs. This paper compares the relationship between the environmental risk financing mechanisms of self-insurance, industry pools, and integrated-insurance policies with the number of environmental liability cases filed against a firm. Using the Principal Agent Model as the basis to follow the expected utility trends of publicly traded corporations, individual company portfolios in the construction and environmental engineering industry are sampled to determine the components of the model. The components of the Principal Agent Model (environmental liability cases as a function of total revenues, total coverage, and annual premium) will demonstrate the relationship of each risk financing mechanism on environmental liability behavior. The empirical study of the Principal Agent Model will demonstrate the ability of environmental risk financing mechanisms to control the environmental behavior of publicly traded firms in the construction and environmental engineering industry. This study will show that self-insurance is the least effective risk financing mechanism in controlling risky environmental behavior, the greatest deflator of risky behavior is found in correctly pricing the cost of monitoring through premiums, and the reduction in risky environmental behavior through total project coverage occurs only when an interested third party is monitoring the activity of the firm.
