AU  - Ajith Pyati
TI  - Hemp and Cotton: A Comparative Look at Fertilizer Use Between the Two Crops
PY  - 1997
PB  - University of California, Berkeley
UR  - https://www.ocf.berkeley.edu/~pkmendez/envsci/projects/1997final/PyatiA_1997.pdf
U1  - PyatiA_1997-page1.pdf
AB  - Cotton is the world’s major fiber crop, but increasing concerns about its detrimental environmental effects, such as the increasing use of fertilizers and pesticides, has opened up the debate on the use of alternative fiber crops, such as hemp. The focus of this paper is to compare the fertilizer requirements for hemp and cotton, and the yields associated with them. United States Department of Agriculture statistics were used for cotton yield and fertilization data, and data from hemp was gathered from experiments conducted during the 1940’s in the midwestern United States. A qualitative comparison of fertilizer inputs and associated yields were conducted, and on small-scale plots, hemp appears to have less fertilizer demands and larger yields than cotton. An expansion of growing area and growth in areas that overlap with cotton should be conducted to give an accurate comparison of the nutrient needs of the two plants.
