AB  - This project quantitatively compares the environmental impact resulting from the
use ofsport utility vehicles (SUVs) and passenger vehicles for commuting in the San
Francisco Bay area. The average number ofpassengers per vehicle, fuel efficiency per person
and quantity ofemissions per person for SUVs and for the total vehicle population. These
estimates are based on data from asample of3000 vehicles observed in different parts ofthe
San Francisco Bay Area. This study has shown that while the average number ofpassengers
per available space carried bySUVs is the same asthe fleet average, SUVs consume more
gasoline and produce more emissions. Therefore, SUVs appear to be less efficient for the
purposes of commuting than an average Bay Area automobile. However, due to sampling
limitations, I can not determine if these results are statistically significant.
