AU  - Justin Victor Remais
TI  - EVALUATING SALICORNIA VIRGINICA PLANTING AT THE ORO LOMA WETLAND RESTORATION PROJECT
PY  - 1997
PB  - University of California, Berkeley
UR  - https://www.ocf.berkeley.edu/~pkmendez/envsci/projects/1997final/RemaisJV_1997.pdf
U1  - RemaisJV_1997-page1.pdf
AB  - Coastal wetlands, such as the Oro Loma Marsh, located in Hayward, California, perform valuable functions for the environment such as supporting productive plant growth, acting as spawning areas for non-game and commercial fishes, providing habitat to rare species, detoxifying water pollutants, and preventing soil erosion. However, human activities, such as salt-extraction and agricultural conversion, have destroyed these wetlands, prompting San Francisco Bay Area agencies to restore them. The Oro Loma Marsh Enhancement Project calls for the breaching of two levees that currently prevent tidal flows from entering the site. Pickleweed (Salicornia virginica) was planted in March,1997 to augment the natural habitat of the salt marsh harvest mouse (Reithrodontomys raviventris) and to control erosion. Experimental plots that varied in location, elevation, orientation, density and method of erosion control were planted to determine which set of planting variables leads to successful establishment of S. virginica populations, minimizes erosion potential, promotes suitable habitat for SMHM, and excludes invading non-native plants. The wetland’s recovery will be monitored using both biological and physical performance indicators, which will allow evaluation of the site’s biota and physical properties (such as plant population distributions, stature, and biomass, as well as soil redox potential, salinity and pH). These indicators will be measured in the restored wetland and compared to measurements from nearby reference sites. Unexpected procedural and natural obstacles, such as miscommunication, exceptionally low precipitation and lack of human resources led to the irreversible damage of 96.2 percent of the planted material. My research experience demonstrates the need for a more organized, committed approach to wetland restoration projects.
