AU  - Heather Schneider
TI  - Regulation of Discharges into State Waters: The Role of Citizen Suits in Ensuring Compliance with NPDES Permits
PY  - 1997
PB  - University of California, Berkeley
UR  - https://www.ocf.berkeley.edu/~pkmendez/envsci/projects/1997final/SchneiderH_1997.pdf
U1  - SchneiderH_1997-page1.pdf
AB  - The Clean Water Act is a federal statute mandating that major companies which discharge waste into state waters comply with federally determined discharge limits. The statute additionally specifies that the permitted companies submit monthly reports, detailing compliance with the permits, to a regional board designed to oversee compliance. There is little incentive for a company to self-report, and therefore monitoring and enforcement are lacking. To enhance compliance, Congress enabled citizens to file suit against violators. However, the number of restrictions placed upon citizens filing suits has hindered their effectiveness. In an effort to test the effectiveness of citizens ensuring compliance, I have examined six permitted oil refineries in the San Francisco Bay area from 1994-1996. Descriptive statistics show that there is a void in enforcement actions against violators. My hypothesis that larger companies are more highly regulated and therefore have fewer violations is supported by my data.
