TI  - The Economic Value of Bair Island: from a wetland functional perspective
PY  - 1997
PB  - University of California, Berkeley
UR  - https://www.ocf.berkeley.edu/~pkmendez/envsci/projects/1997final/WangW_1997.pdf
U1  - WangW_1997-page1.pdf
AB  - The U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service estimates that prior to the European Settlement, California had an approximated 5 millions acres of wetlands. Unfortunately, since 1850, 90% of the wetlands have been drained, filled and diked for agricultural, industrial, and commercial purposes. Not until the early 1970s did people begin to realize the importance of wetlands and to examine them more closely. Studies have been done to calculate the economic value of wetland functions in different locations of the Unites Stated using various techniques. The purpose of this paper is to estimate the use value of Bair Island by examining economic valuation studies that had been done elsewhere in the U.S. between 1971-1994. The result of this study indicates that the current market value does not necessarily reflect the economic value of Bair Island. Furthermore, by draining and converting Bair Island for housing purpose, California will lose approximately $39 million worth of the economic benefits provided by the wetland.
